# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: road-sports
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The **1904–05 Ottawa Hockey Club season**, the club's 20th season of play, lasted from January 7, 1905, until March 11, 1905.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Ottawa won the league championship of the Federal Amateur Hockey League and successfully defended its Stanley Cup championship against all challengers.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] After resigning from the Canadian Amateur Hockey League (CAHL) in January 1904, the club made plans to join the FAHL.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] However, before the season started, the club investigated returning to the CAHL and to helping create a merger of the FAHL with the CAHL.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The teams of the CAHL were opposed to both initiatives and the club played the season in the FAHL.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Two personal tragedies occurred during the off-season.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Jim McGee died in a horse-riding accident in May.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The McGee family did not wish Frank to continue to play hockey with only one good eye but Frank chose to play the season.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Harvey Pulford's wife Annis died giving birth to a son in December 1904.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] In December 1904, the Ottawas signed an agreement to return to Dey's Rink for season and Stanley Cup play.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The Ottawas had been unhappy with the Aberdeen Pavilion and the Dey's Rink management agreed to arena improvement.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Bouse Hutton was ruled ineligible by the Canadian Amateur Athletic Union (CAAU) to play amateur ice hockey.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] He had played with the Ottawa Capitals Lacrosse Club, which was ruled to be a professional team.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] In addition, he had a severe case of quinsy.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Hutton retired from ice hockey, continuing in lacrosse.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Harry Westwick who also had played lacrosse, was deemed eligible by the CAAU to play ice hockey for Ottawa, but was considered a professional by the Ontario Hockey Association (OHA).
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] This meant the cancellation of an exhibition between the Toronto Marlboros and Ottawa prior to the season as Ottawa refused to play without Westwick.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The Dey's Rink still charged the Marlboros for rental of the rink.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Suddy Gilmour did not return for this season, as he went to work lumbering in the Gatineaus.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The Club won the league championship with a record of seven wins and one loss.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The first game, on January 7 versus the Wanderers, was attended by Albert Grey, 4th Earl Grey, the Governor-General of Canada.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Grey dropped the puck for the first face-off.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] It was the first display of ice hockey that he attended.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Frank McGee scored five goals against the Montagnards on February 4.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] An "own goal", by Garnet McDonald of Cornwall, in the February 24, 1905 game was also recorded for Ottawa.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The first interest in a challenge from Dawson City was indicated in a letter from Weldy Young to the *Ottawa Citizen*, in 1900.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The Stanley Cup trustees received a letter from G.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Shannon of Dawson on June 7, 1901, challenging the then-champion Winnipeg Victorias.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Ross wrote back to Dawson, nothing further was heard from the Dawson club until September 9, 1904, when Ross received a challenge from Young for a Dawson City All-Star team to challenge the Silver Seven.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Ross authorized the challenge in December 1904.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] In January 1905, the Dawson City Nuggets travelled 4,000 miles (6,400 km) from the Yukon to Ottawa for a best-of-three Cup challenge series.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The Nuggets actually left Dawson City on December 19, 1904, and travelled on a month-long journey by dog sled (Dawson to Whitehorse), ship (Skagway to Vancouver), and train (Whitehorse to Skagway, and Vancouver to Ottawa).
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] They were no match for the Silver Seven.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Ottawa defeated them in the first game, 9–2.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Numerous Stanley Cup records were then set in game two, including Frank McGee's 14 goals, which included eight consecutive goals scored in less than nine minutes, and a 23–2 rout, the largest margin of victory for any challenge game or Stanley Cup Finals game to date.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Several players playing for Dawson were from the Ottawa area.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Randy McLennan was from Glengarry County, Ontario and had played in a Stanley Cup challenge for Queen's University of Kingston, Ontario.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Another player had Stanley Cup challenge experience: Lorne Hanna, "formerly of the Yukon", had played for Brandon Wheat City in their 1904 challenge of Ottawa.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] After the series, Ottawa held a banquet for Dawson City at the Ottawa Amateur Athletic Association (OAAA) clubhouse.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] There is a Stanley Cup legend that after the banquet, the Stanley Cup was drop kicked into the frozen Rideau Canal nearby and retrieved the next day.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] However, Bill Westwick, *Ottawa Journal* sports editor and the son of Silver Seven player Rat Westwick, and NHL President Frank Calder both deny it ever happened.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] In March 1905, the Rat Portage Thistles issued another challenge to the Senators.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] McGee did not play in the first game and the Thistles crushed Ottawa, 9–3.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] However, he returned to lead the Senators to 4–2 and 5–4 victories in games two and three, respectively.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] McGee returned in game two, with his good forearm wrapped in a cast, and only a light bandage on his broken wrist, to decoy the Thistles.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Alf Smith scored three goals in game two on slow ice, which the Thistles claimed was salted to slow down the Thistles.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] There was hard ice in game three, and the lead exchanged hands several times.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The Thistles led 2–1 at halftime and 3–2 midway through the second half.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Ottawa took a 4–3 lead, before Tommy Phillips scored his third of the game to tie the score.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] However, McGee came through with the winning score late in the game to win it for Ottawa.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Nearly 11,000 attended the series, and sell-outs left spectators outside of Dey's Arena.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Ottawa played game one without two of its top players: Frank McGee and Billy Gilmour.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] In the *Montreal Gazette* report, the Thistles' speed was praised, saying that "once one of the Thistle players had broken away he was hardly in any danger of being caught by an Ottawa forward." Rat Portage scored first but Ottawa scored twice to gain the lead.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Si Griffis then scored three consecutive goals to put the Thistles ahead 4–2 at the half.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] In the second half, the Thistles continued their dominance, scoring four straight before Ottawa replied.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Phillips scored his final goal to make it 9–3 for the Thistles.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The second game was played on heavy, wet, ice.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] This was considered a disadvantage to the Thistles, who were unable to play their style of game, having only skates suited to fast ice.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Bolstered by the return of McGee and Gilmour, Ottawa played a game of "trickery and rough tactics" that they were known for.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Griffis opened the scoring at 16 minutes of the first half.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] A minute later, Smith responded, tying the score.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Hooper scored for Rat Portage two minutes later to put the Thistles again into the lead, but this was countered by two goals from Ottawa's Smith and Gilmour to put Ottawa ahead 3–2 at the half.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] In the second half, only Ottawa was able to score, as Ottawa's Smith completed his hat trick at 18:45 to cement the game for Ottawa.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] McGee did not score, but did his part to intimidate the Thistles with stick work, drawing four penalties.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Dey's Rink was jammed, filled with 3,500 spectators, leaving approximately 1,000 outside on Gladstone Avenue.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The third game was played on hard, fast ice unlike game two.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] McGee came to the fore in scoring, scoring a hat trick, including the game and Cup winner with two minutes to play.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] In the first half, Phillips of Rat Portage scored twice to put the Thistles ahead 2–1 at the half.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Smith of Ottawa opened the scoring in the second, matched by Hooper eight minutes later.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] McGee and Westwick scored to put Ottawa ahead 4–3 but Phillips tied it at 4 with four minutes to play.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] McGee won the game with his third goal, converting a pass from Pulford with two and a half minutes to go.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] The *Montreal Gazette* report praised the quality of the game and Harvey Pulford in particular.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] † Substitute/on team picture/dressed, but did not play &-Missing from the team picture.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] Weldy Young, a former member of the Ottawa team in the 1890s, and the captain of the Dawson City team, engraved his name on the Cup with a pen knife.
[src:road-sports/1904-05-ottawa-hockey-club-season] He had missed playing for Dawson as he was working in the federal election, although he did arrive in Ottawa during the series.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] An **aircraft carrier** is a warship designed to carry, launch, recover and support aircraft at sea, equipped with a full-length flight deck and hangar facilities that allow it to serve as a mobile, seagoing airbase.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Typically it is the capital ship of a fleet (known as a carrier battle group), as it allows a naval force to project seaborne air power far from national territory without depending on local airfields for the staging of aircraft operations.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] While heavier fixed-wing aircraft such as airlifters, gunships and bombers have been launched from aircraft carriers, these aircraft do not often land on a carrier due to flight deck limitations.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier, along with its onboard aircraft and defensive ancillary weapons, is the largest weapon system ever created.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] By their tactical prowess, mobility, autonomy and the variety of operational means, aircraft carriers are often the centerpiece of modern naval warfare, and have significant diplomatic influence in deterrence, command of the sea and air supremacy.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the Second World War, the aircraft carrier has replaced the battleship in the role of flagship of a fleet, and largely transformed naval battles from gunfire to beyond-visual-range air strikes.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies use several variants of the aircraft carrier, sometimes categorized as sub-types of aircraft carriers and sometimes as distinct types of aviation-capable ships.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft carriers may be classified according to the type of aircraft they carry and their operational assignments.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Navies have a variety of classification systems for their ships, and a definitive number of current aircraft carriers depends on the specific criteria.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] As of July 2026 there are 9 navies operating 24 active vessels designated by their respective navies as either an "Aircraft Carrier" or "Aircraft Cruiser".
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] These range in tonnage from the United States' 100,000 tonne USS *Gerald R.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford* to Brazil's 21,000 tonne NAM *Atlantico*.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of the types listed here are not strictly defined as aircraft carriers by some sources.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] A fleet carrier is intended to operate with the main fleet and usually provides an offensive capability.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] These are the largest carriers capable of fast speeds.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] By comparison, escort carriers were developed to provide defense for convoys of ships.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] They were smaller and slower with lower numbers of aircraft carried.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Most were built from mercantile hulls or, in the case of merchant aircraft carriers, were bulk cargo ships with a flight deck added on top.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Light aircraft carriers were fast enough to operate with the main fleet but of smaller size with reduced aircraft capacity.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Soviet aircraft carrier *Admiral Kusnetsov* was termed a "heavy aircraft-carrying cruiser".
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was primarily a legal construct to avoid the limitations of the Montreux Convention preventing 'aircraft carriers' transiting the Turkish Straits between the Soviet Black Sea bases and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] These ships, while sized in the range of large fleet carriers, were designed to deploy alone or with escorts.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition to supporting fighter aircraft and helicopters, they provide both strong defensive weaponry and heavy offensive missiles equivalent to a guided-missile cruiser.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The appellation "supercarrier" is not an official designation with any national navy, but a term used predominantly by the media and typically when reporting on larger and more advanced carrier types.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] It is also used when comparing carriers of various sizes and capabilities, both current and past.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] It was first used by *The New York Times* in 1938, in an article about the Royal Navy's HMS *Ark Royal*, that had a length of 800 feet (244 m), a displacement of 22,000 tons and was designed to carry 72 aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since then, aircraft carriers have consistently grown in size, both in length and displacement, as well as improved capabilities; in defense, sensors, electronic warfare, propulsion, range, launch and recovery systems, number and types of aircraft carried and number of sorties flown per day.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first aircraft carrier over 80,000 tonnes full-load displacement was the USS Forrestal launched in 1954.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] In total, the US Navy has had 5 different classes of aircraft carrier of this size definition, the Forrestal class, Kitty Hawk class, the Enterprise class, the Nimitz class and Gerald R Ford Class, two of which were conventional steam-powered and three nuclear-powered.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] USS *Enterprise*, launched in 1960, was the first carrier over 90,000 tonnes full load displacement and *Nimitz*, launched in 1972, was the first over 100,000 tonnes displacement.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] A total of 22 supercarriers have been launched by the US Navy since 1954, with 11 currently in service.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Both China (Type 003) and the United Kingdom (Queen Elizabeth class) have carriers in service with displacements from 80,000 to 85,000 tonnes and lengths from 280 to 320 meters (920 to 1,050 ft) which are described as "supercarriers".
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] France is also developing a new aircraft carrier (PANG) which is to have a full load displacement of 80,000 tonnes and will be considered a supercarrier.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The largest supercarrier in service as of 2024 is the US Navy's USS Gerald R.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford, with full load displacement of around 100,000 tons, length of 337 meters (1,106 ft) and capabilities that exceed those of any other class.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] A US Navy proposal for an aircraft carrier concept with a length of 1,310 feet and a displacement of 500,000 tons full load at a cost of $828 million in 1976 dollars.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Project Habakkuk could be considered an early proposal for an "ultracarrier".
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Several systems of identification symbol for aircraft carriers and related types of ship have been used.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] These include the pennant numbers used by the Royal Navy, Commonwealth countries, and Europe, along with the hull classification symbols used by the US and Canada.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Two months later, on 18 January 1911, Ely landed his Curtiss Pusher airplane on a platform on the armored cruiser USS *Pennsylvania* anchored in San Francisco Bay.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seaplane tender support ships came next, with the French *Foudre* of 1911.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Early in World War I, the Imperial Japanese Navy ship *Wakamiya* conducted the world's first carrier-launched air raid: on 6 September 1914, the *Wakamiya* used its crane to lower Farman seaplanes into the water.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Wakamiya* attacked the Austro-Hungarian cruiser SMS *Kaiserin Elisabeth* and the Imperial German gunboat *Jaguar* in Jiaozhou Bay off Qingdao; neither was hit.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first attack using an air-launched torpedo occurred on 2 August, when a torpedo was fired by Flight Commander Charles Edmonds from a Short Type 184 seaplane, launched from the seaplane carrier HMS *Ben-my-Chree*.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first carrier-launched airstrike was the Tondern raid in July 1918.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seven Sopwith Camels were launched from the battlecruiser HMS *Furious*, which had been completed as a carrier by replacing her planned forward turret with a flight deck and hangar prior to commissioning.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Camels attacked and damaged the German airbase at Tondern, Germany (modern day Tønder, Denmark), and destroyed two zeppelin airships.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first landing of an airplane on a moving ship was by Squadron Commander Edwin Harris Dunning, when he landed his Sopwith Pup on HMS *Furious* in Scapa Flow, Orkney, on 2 August 1917.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Landing on the forward flight deck required the pilot to approach round the ship's superstructure, a difficult and dangerous manoeuver, and Dunning was later killed when his airplane was thrown overboard while attempting another landing on *Furious*.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] HMS *Furious* was modified again when her rear turret was removed and another flight deck added over a second hangar for landing aircraft over the stern.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Her funnel and superstructure remained intact, however, and turbulence from the funnel and superstructure was severe enough that only three landing attempts were successful before further attempts were forbidden.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] This experience prompted the development of vessels with a flush deck and produced the first large fleet ships.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] In 1918, HMS *Argus* became the world's first carrier capable of launching and recovering naval aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] As a result of the Washington Naval Treaty of 1922, which limited the construction of new heavy surface combat ships, most early aircraft carriers were conversions of ships that were laid down (or had served) as different ship types: cargo ships, cruisers, battlecruisers, or battleships.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] These conversions gave rise to the USS *Langley* in 1922, the US *Lexington*-class aircraft carriers (1927), Japanese *Akagi* and *Kaga*, and British *Courageous* class (of which *Furious* was one).
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Specialist carrier evolution was well underway, with several navies ordering and building warships that were purposefully designed to function as aircraft carriers by the mid-1920s.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] This resulted in the commissioning of ships such as the Japanese *Hōshō* (1922), HMS *Hermes* (1924, although laid down in 1918 before *Hōshō*), and *Béarn* (1927).
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] During World War II, these ships would become known as fleet carriers.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier dramatically changed naval warfare in World War II, because air power was becoming a significant factor in warfare.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The advent of aircraft as focal weapons was driven by the superior range, flexibility, and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] They had greater range and precision than naval guns, making them highly effective.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The versatility of the carrier was demonstrated in November 1940, when HMS *Illustrious* launched a long-range strike on the Italian fleet at their base in Taranto, signalling the beginning of the effective and highly mobile aircraft strikes.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] This operation in the shallow water harbor incapacitated three of the six anchored battleships at a cost of two torpedo bombers.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] World War II in the Pacific Ocean involved clashes between aircraft carrier fleets.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Japanese surprise attack on the American Pacific fleet at Pearl Harbor naval and air bases on Sunday, 7 December 1941, was a clear illustration of the power projection capability afforded by a large force of modern carriers.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Concentrating six carriers in a single unit turned naval history about, as no other nation had fielded anything comparable.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] In the "Doolittle Raid", on 18 April 1942, the US Navy carrier USS *Hornet* sailed to within 650 nautical miles (1,200 km) of Japan and launched 16 B-25 Mitchell medium bombers from her deck in a demonstrative retaliatory strike on the mainland, including the capital, Tokyo.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] However, the vulnerability of carriers compared to traditional capital ships was illustrated by the sinking of HMS *Glorious* by German battleships during the Norwegian campaign in 1940.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] This new-found importance of naval aviation forced nations to create a number of carriers, in efforts to provide air superiority cover for every major fleet to ward off enemy aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] This extensive usage led to the development and construction of 'light' carriers.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Escort aircraft carriers, such as USS *Bogue*, were sometimes purpose-built but most were converted from merchant ships as a stop-gap measure to provide anti-submarine air support for convoys and amphibious invasions.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following this concept, light aircraft carriers built by the US, such as USS *Independence* (commissioned in 1943), represented a larger, more "militarized" version of the escort carrier.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although with similar complement to escort carriers, they had the advantage of speed from their converted cruiser hulls.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The UK 1942 Design Light Fleet Carrier was designed for building quickly by civilian shipyards and with an expected service life of about 3 years.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] They served the Royal Navy during the war, and the hull design was chosen for nearly all aircraft carrier equipped navies after the war, until the 1980s.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Emergencies also spurred the creation or conversion of highly unconventional aircraft carriers.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] CAM ships were cargo-carrying merchant ships that could launch (but not retrieve) a single fighter aircraft from a catapult to defend the convoy from long range land-based German aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Noteworthy converted carriers were also USS *Sable* (IX-81) and USS *Wolverine* (IX-64) that both operated on the Great Lakes for training duties and were converted from paddle steamers, making them the only aircraft carriers with this type of propulsion.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before World War II, international naval treaties of 1922, 1930, and 1936 limited the size of capital ships, including carriers.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since World War II, aircraft carrier designs have increased in size to accommodate a steady increase in aircraft size.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The large, modern *Nimitz* class of US Navy carriers has a displacement nearly four times that of the World War II–era USS *Enterprise*, yet its complement of aircraft is roughly the same—a consequence of the steadily increasing size and weight of individual military aircraft over the years.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Today's aircraft carriers are so expensive that some nations which operate them risk significant economic and military impact if a carrier is lost.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies that operate such aircraft carriers treat them as capital ships of fleets, a role previously held by the galleons, ships-of-the-line and battleships.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] This change took place during World War II in response to air power becoming a significant factor in warfare, driven by the superior range, flexibility and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following the war, carrier operations continued to increase in size and importance, and along with, carrier designs also increased in size and ability.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of these larger carriers, dubbed by the media as "supercarriers", displacing 75,000 tons or greater, have become the pinnacle of carrier development.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some are powered by nuclear reactors and form the core of a fleet designed to operate far from home.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Amphibious assault ships, such as the *Wasp* and *Mistral* classes, serve the purpose of carrying and landing Marines, and operate a large contingent of helicopters for that purpose.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Also known as "commando carriers" or "helicopter carriers", many have the capability to operate VSTOL aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The threatening role of aircraft carriers has a place in modern asymmetric warfare, like the gunboat diplomacy of the past.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers also facilitate quick and precise projections of overwhelming military power into such local and regional conflicts.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Lacking the firepower of other warships, carriers by themselves are considered vulnerable to attack by other ships, aircraft, submarines, or missiles.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The resulting group of ships is often termed a carrier strike group, battle group, carrier group, or carrier battle group.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] There is a view among some military pundits that modern anti-ship weapons systems, such as torpedoes and missiles, or even ballistic missiles with nuclear warheads have made aircraft carriers and carrier groups too vulnerable for modern combat.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers are large and long ships, although there is a high degree of variation depending on their intended role and aircraft complement.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The size of the carrier has varied over history and among navies, to cater to the various roles that global climates have demanded from naval aviation.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Regardless of size, the ship itself must house their complement of aircraft, with space for launching, storing, and maintaining them.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Space is also required for the large crew, supplies (food, munitions, fuel, engineering parts), and propulsion.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] US and French aircraft carriers are notable for having nuclear reactors powering their systems and propulsion.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The top of the carrier is the flight deck, where aircraft are launched and recovered.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the starboard side of this is the island, where ship navigation from the bridge and air traffic control from flyco are controlled and (in non-nuclear powered vessels), provides the location of the ship's funnel(s).
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Queen Elizabeth*-class has two island structures; the forward island contains the navigation bridge, while the aft structure houses flyco.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The constraints of constructing a flight deck strongly affect the role of a given carrier, as they influence the weight, type, and configuration of the aircraft that may be launched.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, assisted launch mechanisms are used primarily for heavy aircraft, especially those loaded with air-to-ground weapons.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR is most commonly used on US Navy fleet carriers as it allows the deployment of heavy jets with full load-outs, especially on ground-attack missions.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] STOVL is used by other navies because it is cheaper to operate and still provides good deployment capability for fighter aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Due to the busy nature of the flight deck, only 20 or so aircraft may be on it at any one time.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] A hangar storage several decks below the flight deck is where most aircraft are kept, and aircraft are taken from the lower storage decks to the flight deck through the use of an elevator.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The hangar is usually quite large and can take up several decks of vertical space.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Munitions are commonly stored on the lower decks because they are highly explosive.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Usually this is below the waterline so that the area can be flooded in case of emergency.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] As "runways at sea", aircraft carriers have a flat-top flight deck, which launches and recovers aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft launch forward, into the wind, and are recovered from astern.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Creating such a surface at sea poses constraints on the carrier.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the size of the vessel is a fundamental limitation on runway length.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] This affects take-off procedure, as a shorter runway length of the deck requires that aircraft accelerate more quickly to gain lift.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] This either requires a thrust boost, a vertical component to its velocity, or a reduced take-off load (to lower mass).
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The differing types of deck configuration, as above, influence the structure of the flight deck.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The form of launch assistance a carrier provides is strongly related to the types of aircraft embarked and the design of the carrier itself.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are two main philosophies to keep the deck short: add thrust to the aircraft, such as using a Catapult Assisted Take-Off (CATO-); and changing the direction of the airplanes' thrust, as in Vertical and/or Short Take-Off (V/STO-).
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the recovery side of the flight deck, the adaptation to the aircraft load-out is mirrored.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Non-VTOL or conventional aircraft cannot decelerate on their own, and almost all carriers using them must have arrested-recovery systems (-BAR, e.g.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR or STOBAR) to recover their aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft that are landing extend a tailhook that catches on arrestor wires stretched across the deck to bring themselves to a stop in a short distance.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] If the aircraft are VTOL-capable or helicopters, they do not need to decelerate and hence there is no such need.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The arrested-recovery system has used an angled deck since the 1950s because, in case the aircraft does not catch the arresting wire, the short deck allows easier take off by reducing the number of objects between the aircraft and the end of the runway.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] It also has the advantage of separating the recovery operation area from the launch area.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Helicopters and aircraft capable of vertical or short take-off and landing (V/STOL) usually recover by coming abreast of the carrier on the port side and then using their hover capability to move over the flight deck and land vertically without the need for arresting gear.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers steam at speed, up to 35 knots (65 km/h; 40 mph) into the wind during flight deck operations to increase wind speed over the deck to a safe minimum.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] This increase in effective wind speed provides a higher launch airspeed for aircraft at the end of the catapult stroke or ski-jump, as well as making recovery safer by reducing the difference between the relative speeds of the aircraft and ship.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the early 1950s on conventional carriers it has been the practice to recover aircraft at an angle to port of the axial line of the ship.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The primary function of this angled deck is to allow aircraft that miss the arresting wires, referred to as a bolter, to become airborne again without the risk of hitting aircraft parked forward.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The angled deck allows the installation of one or two "waist" catapults in addition to the two bow cats.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] An angled deck also improves launch and recovery cycle flexibility with the option of simultaneous launching and recovery of aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Conventional ("tailhook") aircraft rely upon a landing signal officer (LSO, radio call sign 'paddles') to monitor the aircraft's approach, visually gauge glideslope, attitude, and airspeed, and transmit that data to the pilot.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before the angled deck emerged in the 1950s, LSOs used colored paddles to signal corrections to the pilot (hence the nickname).
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] From the late 1950s onward, visual landing aids such as the optical landing system have provided information on proper glide slope, but LSOs still transmit voice calls to approaching pilots by radio.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Key personnel involved in the flight deck include the shooters, the handler, and the air boss.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Shooters are naval aviators or naval flight officers and are responsible for launching aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The handler works just inside the island from the flight deck and is responsible for the movement of aircraft before launching and after recovery.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The captain of the ship spends most of his time one level below primary on the Navigation Bridge.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Below this is the Flag Bridge, designated for the embarked admiral and his staff.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] To facilitate working on the flight deck of a US aircraft carrier, the sailors wear colored shirts that designate their responsibilities.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are at least seven different colors worn by flight deck personnel for modern United States Navy carrier air operations.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carrier operations of other nations use similar color schemes.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The superstructure of a carrier (such as the bridge, flight control tower) are concentrated in a relatively small area called an *island*, a feature pioneered on HMS *Hermes* in 1923.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] While the island is usually built on the starboard side of the flight deck, the Japanese aircraft carriers *Akagi* and *Hiryū* had their islands built on the port side.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Very few carriers have been designed or built without an island.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *flush deck* configuration proved to have significant drawbacks, primary of which was management of the exhaust from the power plant.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Fumes coming across the deck were a major issue in USS *Langley*.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition, lack of an island meant difficulties managing the flight deck, performing air traffic control, a lack of radar housing placements and problems with navigating and controlling the ship itself.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another deck structure that can be seen is a ski-jump ramp at the forward end of the flight deck.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was first developed to help launch short take off vertical landing (STOVL) aircraft take off at far higher weights than is possible with a vertical or rolling takeoff on flat decks.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Originally developed by the Royal Navy, it since has been adopted by many navies for smaller carriers.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski-jump ramp works by converting some of the forward rolling movement of the aircraft into vertical velocity and is sometimes combined with the aiming of jet thrust partly downward.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] This allows heavily loaded and fueled aircraft a few more precious seconds to attain sufficient air velocity and lift to sustain normal flight.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Without a ski-jump, launching fully-loaded and fueled aircraft such as the Harrier would not be possible on a smaller flat deck ship before either stalling out or crashing directly into the sea.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although STOVL aircraft are capable of taking off vertically from a spot on the deck, using the ramp and a running start is far more fuel efficient and permits a heavier launch weight.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] As catapults are unnecessary, carriers with this arrangement reduce weight, complexity, and space needed for complex steam or electromagnetic launching equipment.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Vertical landing aircraft also remove the need for arresting cables and related hardware.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Russian, Chinese, and Indian carriers include a ski-jump ramp for launching lightly loaded conventional fighter aircraft but recover using traditional carrier arresting cables and a tailhook on their aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the Russian Sukhoi Su-33 is only able to launch from the carrier *Admiral Kuznetsov* with a minimal armament and fuel load.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another disadvantage is on mixed flight deck operations where helicopters are also present, such as on a US landing helicopter dock or landing helicopter assault amphibious assault ship.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski jump is not included as this would eliminate one or more helicopter landing areas; this flat deck limits the loading of Harriers but is somewhat mitigated by the longer rolling start provided by a long flight deck compared to many STOVL carriers.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United States operates 11 nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carriers, with a total combined deck space over twice that of all other nations combined as of 2016.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] China operates one catapult-assisted aircraft carrier and two ski-jump carriers.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United Kingdom and India each currently operate two ski-jump aircraft carriers, and France operates one nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carrier.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Russia deploys one ski-jump carrier, although it has not been operational since 2017.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the US operates nine large amphibious assault ships with the capability to launch vertical/short takeoff and landing (V/STOL) aircraft, and China operates four amphibious assault ships of a similar size as helicopter carriers.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Italy operates two light V/STOL carriers, and both Spain and Iran operate one V/STOL aircraft-carrying assault ship.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Helicopter carriers are also operated by Japan (4, two converting to operate V/STOL fighters) France (3), Australia (2), Egypt (2), South Korea (2), Thailand (1), Brazil (1) and Iran (1).
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Future aircraft carriers are under construction or planned by China, France, India, Italy, Russia, South Korea, and the US.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Royal Australian Navy operates two *Canberra*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two-ship class, based on the Spanish vessel *Juan Carlos I* and built by Navantia and BAE Systems Australia, represents the largest ships ever built for the Royal Australian Navy.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMAS *Canberra* underwent sea trials in late 2013 and was commissioned in 2014.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Her sister ship, HMAS *Adelaide*, was commissioned in December 2015.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Australian ships retain the ski-ramp from the *Juan Carlos I* design, although the RAN has not acquired carrier-based fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2017, the Brazilian Navy confirmed the purchase of HMS *Ocean* for (GBP) £84.6 million (equivalent to R$359.5M and US$113.2M) and renamed her *Atlântico*.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship was decommissioned from Royal Navy service in March 2018.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Brazilian Navy commissioned the carrier on 29 June 2018 in the United Kingdom.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] After undertaking a period of maintenance in the UK, the ship travelled to its new home port, Rio de Janeiro Navy Arsenal (AMRJ) to be fully operational by 2020.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Before leaving HMNB Devonport for her new homeport in Rio's AMRJ, *Atlântico* underwent operational sea training under the Royal Navy's Flag Officer Sea Training (FOST) program.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] China has had a long-term plan to operate six large aircraft carriers with two carriers per fleet.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is planning a class of eight LHD vessels, the Type 075 (NATO reporting name Yushen-class landing helicopter assault).
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] This is a class of amphibious assault ship under construction by the Hudong–Zhonghua Shipbuilding company.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first ship was commissioned in April 2021.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is also planning a modified class of the same concept, the Type 076 landing helicopter dock, that will be equipped with an electromagnetic catapult system and will likely support launching unmanned combat aerial vehicles.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Egypt signed a contract with French shipbuilder DCNS to buy two *Mistral*-class helicopter carriers for approximately 950 million euros.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two ships were originally to be sold to Russia, but the deal was cancelled by France due to the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2014.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 2 June 2016, Egypt received the first of two helicopter carriers acquired in October 2015, the landing helicopter dock *Gamal Abdel Nasser*.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The flag transfer ceremony took place in the presence of Egyptian and French Navies' chiefs of staff, chairman and chief executive officers of both DCNS and STX France, and senior Egyptian and French officials.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 16 September 2016, DCNS delivered the second of two helicopter carriers, the landing helicopter dock *Anwar El Sadat* which also participated in a joint military exercise with the French Navy before arriving at her home port of Alexandria.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The French Navy operates the 42,000-tonne nuclear-powered aircraft carrier, *Charles de Gaulle*.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Commissioned in 2001, she is the flagship of the French Navy.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship carries a complement of Dassault Rafale M and E-2C Hawkeye aircraft, EC725 Caracal and AS532 Cougar helicopters for combat search and rescue, as well as modern electronics and Aster missiles.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] She is a CATOBAR-type carrier that uses two 75 m C13-3 steam catapults of a shorter version of the catapult system installed on the US *Nimitz*-class carriers, one catapult at the bow and one across the front of the landing area.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the French Navy operates three *Mistral*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] In October 2018, the French Ministry of Defence began an 18-month €40 million study for the replacement of the French aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* sometime after 2030.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, President Macron announced that construction of the next generation carrier would begin in around 2025 with sea trials to start in about 2036.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is planned to have a displacement of around 75,000 tons and to carry about 32 next-generation fighters, two to three E-2D Advanced Hawkeyes and a yet-to-be-determined number of unmanned carrier air vehicles.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has plans for a third carrier, INS *Vishal*, also known as *Indigenous Aircraft Carrier 2 (IAC-2)* with a displacement of over 65,000 tonnes and is planned with a CATOBAR system to launch and recover heavier aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has also issued a request for information (RFI) to procure four Landing helicopter dock displacing 30,000–40,000 tons with a capacity to operate 12 medium lift special ops and two heavy lift helicopters and troops for amphibious operations.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] On February 6, 2025, the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) accepted the IRIS *Shahid Bagheri*, a 41,978-tonne drone UAV carrier converted from a container ship.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] was launched August 2013 and commissioned March 2015.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] the Japanese defense ministry's position is "We are not creating carrier air wings or carrier air squadrons" similar to the US Navy.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] from land bases; according to the 2020 Japanese Defense Ministry white paper the STOVL model was chosen for the JASDF due the lack of appropriately long runways to support air superiority capability across all of Japanese airspace.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] ships "for cooperation and advice on how to operate the fighter on the deck of the modified ships".
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] , marking 75 years since fixed-wing aircraft operated from a Japanese carrier.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Portuguese Navy plans, for the second half of 2026, to receive the NRP *D.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] João II*, a platform ship capable of operating aerial, surface and underwater drones, medium helicopters (Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk) and heavy helicopters (EH101 Merlin) helicopters of the Portuguese Air Force.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] One STOBAR carrier: *Admiral Flota Sovetskogo Soyuza Kuznetsov*: 55,000-tonne *Kuznetsov*-class STOBAR aircraft carrier.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Launched in 1985 as *Tbilisi*, renamed and operational from 1995.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Without catapults she can launch and recover lightly fueled naval fighters for air defense or anti-ship missions but not heavy conventional bombing strikes.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Officially designated an aircraft carrying cruiser, she is unique in carrying a heavy cruiser's complement of defensive weapons and large P-700 Granit offensive missiles.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The P-700 systems will be removed in the coming refit to enlarge her below decks aviation facilities as well as upgrading her defensive systems.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship has been out of service and in repairs since 2018.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The most recent projection stated that repairs would be completed and the ship transferred back to the Russian Navy sometime in 2024, however this projection has not been met as of July 2025, and no updates have been provided.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Russian government has been considering the potential replacement of *Admiral Kuznetsov* for some time and has considered the Shtorm-class aircraft carrier as a possible option.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] This carrier will be a hybrid of CATOBAR and STOBAR, given the fact that she uses both systems of launching aircraft.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is expected to cost between $1.8 billion and $5.63 billion.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2020, the project had not yet been approved and, given the financial costs, it was unclear whether it would be made a priority over other elements of Russian naval modernization.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] A class of 2 LHD, Project 23900 is planned and an official keel laying ceremony for the project happened on 20 July 2020.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two *Dokdo*-class 18,860-tonne full deck amphibious assault ships with hospital and well deck and facilities to serve as fleet flagships.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] South Korea had set tentative plans for procuring two light aircraft carriers by 2033, which would help make the ROKN a blue water navy.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, details of South Korea's planned carrier program (CVX) were finalized.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] A vessel of about 40,000 tons is envisaged carrying about 20 F-35B fighters as well as future maritime attack helicopters.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Service entry had been anticipated in the early 2030s.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] In 2025 the program was cancelled and replaced with a drone carrier program.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] One offshore helicopter support ship: HTMS *Chakri Naruebet* helicopter carrier: 11,400-tonne STOVL carrier based on Spanish *Príncipe de Asturias* design.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AV-8S Matador/Harrier STOVL fighter wing, mostly inoperable by 1999, was retired from service without replacement in 2006.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2010, the ship is used for helicopter operations and for disaster relief.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* is a 27,079-tonne amphibious assault ship (LHD) (outfitted as drone carrier) of the Turkish Navy that can be configured as a 24,660-tonne V/STOL aircraft carrier.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Construction began on 30 April 2016 by Sedef Shipbuilding Inc. at their Istanbul shipyard.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* was commissioned with a ceremony on 10 April 2023.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of a sister ship, to be named TCG *Trakya*, is currently being planned by the Turkish Navy.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Sikorsky S-70B Seahawk and the Bell AH-1 SuperCobra are the two main types of helicopters used on TCG *Anadolu*, with the occasional use of CH-47F Chinook helicopters of the Turkish Army during military exercises and operations.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AH-1W Super Cobras will eventually be complemented and replaced by the TAI T929 ATAK 2.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The jet-powered, low-observable drone Bayraktar MIUS Kızılelma and the MALE UAV Bayraktar TB3 are two UCAVs that are specifically designed and manufactured by Baykar Technologies to be used on TCG *Anadolu*.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The maiden flight of TAI Anka-3 (also part of Project MIUS), a jet-powered, flying wing type UCAV with stealth technology, was successfully completed on 28 December 2023.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 19 November 2024, Baykar Bayraktar TB3 UCAV successfully took-off from the flight deck of TCG *Anadolu* and landed on the ship.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] It was the first time a fixed-wing unmanned aircraft of this size and class had successfully landed on a short-runway landing helicopter dock, without the use of an arresting gear.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 3 January 2024, the Turkish government approved the plan for the design and construction of a larger aircraft carrier, named the *MUGEM*-class.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 15 February 2024, the Design and Projects Office of the Turkish Navy announced that it will be a STOBAR aircraft carrier with an overall length of 285 metres (935 ft), beam of 72 metres (236 ft), draught of 10.1 metres (33 ft), and displacement of 60,000 tons.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is to have a combined diesel–electric and gas (CODLAG) propulsion system and a maximum speed of more than 25 knots (29 mph; 46 km/h).
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of the first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier began on 2 January 2025.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier is being built at the Istanbul Naval Shipyard.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two 80,600-tonne (est. full load) *Queen Elizabeth*-class STOVL carriers which operate the F-35 Lightning II.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMS *Queen Elizabeth* was commissioned in December 2017 and HMS *Prince of Wales* in December 2019.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The current US fleet of *Nimitz*-class carriers will be followed into service (and in some cases replaced) by the *Gerald R.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is expected that the ships will be more automated in an effort to reduce the amount of funding required to maintain and operate the vessels.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The main new features are implementation of Electromagnetic Aircraft Launch System (EMALS) (which replaces the old steam catapults) and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] In terms of future carrier developments, Congress has discussed the possibility of accelerating the phasing-out of one or more *Nimitz*-class carriers, postponing or canceling the procurement of CVN-81 and CVN-82, or modifying the purchase contract.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Following the deactivation of USS *Enterprise* in December 2012, the US fleet comprised 10 fleet carriers, but that number increased back to 11 with the commissioning of *Gerald R.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The House Armed Services Seapower subcommittee on 24 July 2007, recommended seven or eight new carriers (one every four years).
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] However, the debate has deepened over budgeting for the $12–14.5 billion (plus $12 billion for development and research) for the 100,000-tonne *Gerald R.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Ford*-class carrier (estimated service 2017) compared to the smaller $2 billion 45,000-tonne *America*-class amphibious assault ships, which are able to deploy squadrons of F-35Bs.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first of this class, USS *America*, is now in active service with another, USS *Tripoli*, and 9 more are planned.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] In a report to Congress in February 2018, the Navy stated it intends to maintain a "12 CVN force" as part of its 30-year acquisition plan.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] A few aircraft carriers have been preserved as museum ships.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently portrayed in a number of Hollywood films including *Midway* (2019) and the carrier USS *Nimitz* is centrally featured in the science fiction film *The Final Countdown* (1980).
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The original film version about the Battle at Midway was made in England and titled *Midway* (1976).
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently featured in both *Top Gun* and *Top Gun: Maverick* as providing the launch sites and mission operations support for the fighter operations seen in both films.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Japanese aircraft carriers involved in the attack on Pearl Harbor are featured in the 1970 film *Tora!
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] Tora!* as well as the more recent film from 2001 *Pearl Harbor*.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier USS *Ronald Reagan* makes a cameo appearance at the end of the 2012 science fiction film *Battleship*.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] In the 2025 film *Mission: Impossible – The Final Reckoning*, the aircraft carrier USS *George Bush* is featured as delivering its special agent to a submarine rendezvous with the nuclear-powered USS *Ohio* in the Bering Straits by Alaska.
[src:road-sports/aircraft-carrier-p02] The 50-minute documentary titled *City of Steel: Carrier* was released by the Discovery Channel in 2000 covering the final months of building and inspecting the USS *Harry Truman* through its commissioning by President Bill Clinton.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] American football evolved in the United States, originating from the sports of soccer and rugby.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between two college teams, Rutgers and Princeton, using rules based on the rules of soccer at the time; by 1875, the sport had adopted rules similar to rugby union.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A set of rule changes drawn up from 1880 onward by Walter Camp, the "Father of American Football", established concepts that would define the sport, among them the snap, the line of scrimmage, eleven-player teams, and the concept of downs.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Later rule changes legalized the forward pass, created the neutral zone, and specified the size and shape of the football.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The modern sport is closely related to Canadian football, which evolved in parallel with and at the same time as the American game; the two sports are considered the primary variants of gridiron football.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] American football is the most popular sport in the United States; the most popular forms of the game are professional and college football, with the other major levels being high school and youth football.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Over a million Americans played college or high school football in 2022, and the National Football League (NFL) has one of the highest average attendance of any professional sports league in the world.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Its championship game, the Super Bowl, ranks among the most-watched club sporting events globally.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Other professional and amateur leagues exist worldwide, but the sport does not have the international popularity of other American sports like baseball or basketball; the sport maintains a growing following in the rest of North America, Europe, Brazil, and Japan.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Flag football, a variant of the sport, will be played at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In the United States, American football is referred to as "football".
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The term "football" was officially established in the rulebook for the 1876 college football season, when the sport first shifted from soccer-style rules to rugby-style rules.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Although it could easily have been called "rugby" at this point, Harvard, one of the primary proponents of the rugby-style game, compromised and did not request the name of the sport be changed to "rugby".
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The terms "gridiron" or "American football" are favored in English-speaking countries where other types of football are popular, such as the United Kingdom, Ireland, New Zealand, and Australia.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] American football evolved from the sports of rugby and soccer.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Rugby, like American football, is a sport in which two competing teams vie for control of a ball, which can be kicked through a set of goalposts or run into the opponent's goal area to score points.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] What is considered to be the first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between Rutgers and Princeton, two college teams.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] They consisted of 25 players per team and used a round ball that could not be picked up or carried.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] It could, however, be kicked or batted with the feet, hands, head, or sides, with the objective being to advance it into the opponent's goal.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Collegiate play continued for several years with games played using the rules of the host school.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Representatives of Yale, Columbia, Princeton and Rutgers met on October 19, 1873, to create a standard set of rules for use by all schools.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Teams were set at 20 players each, and fields of 400 by 250 feet (122 m × 76 m) were specified.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Harvard abstained from the conference, as they favored a rugby-style game that allowed running with the ball.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] An 1875 Harvard–Yale game played under rugby-style rules was observed by two Princeton athletes who were impressed by it.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] They introduced the sport to Princeton, a feat the Professional Football Researchers Association compared to "selling refrigerators to Eskimos".
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Princeton, Harvard, Yale, and Columbia then agreed to intercollegiate play using a form of rugby union rules with a modified scoring system.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] These schools formed the Intercollegiate Football Association, although Yale did not join until 1879.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Yale player Walter Camp, now regarded as the "Father of American Football", secured rule changes in 1880 that reduced the size of each team from 15 to 11 players and instituted the snap to replace the chaotic and inconsistent scrum.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] While the game between Rutgers and Princeton is commonly considered the first American football game, several years prior in 1862, the Oneida Football Club formed as the oldest known football club in the United States.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The team consisted of graduates of Boston's elite preparatory schools and played from 1862 to 1865.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The introduction of the snap resulted in an unexpected consequence.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Before the snap, the strategy had been to punt if a scrum resulted in a bad field position.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] However, a group of Princeton players realized that, as the snap was uncontested, they could now hold the ball indefinitely to prevent their opponent from scoring.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In 1881, in a game between Yale and Princeton, both teams used this strategy to maintain their undefeated records.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Each team held the ball, gaining no ground, for an entire half, resulting in a 0–0 tie.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] This "block game" proved extremely unpopular with both teams' spectators and fans.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A rule change was necessary to prevent this strategy from taking hold, and a reversion to the scrum was considered.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] However, Camp successfully proposed a rule in 1882 that limited each team to three downs, or tackles, to advance the ball 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Failure to advance the ball the required distance within those three downs would result in control of the ball being forfeited to the other team.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] This change effectively made American football a separate sport from rugby, and the resulting five-yard lines added to the field to measure distances made it resemble a gridiron in appearance.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Other major rule changes included a reduction of the field size to 110 by 53+1⁄3 yards (100.6 m × 48.8 m) and the adoption of a scoring system that awarded four points for a touchdown, two for a safety and a goal following a touchdown, and five for a goal from the field.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Additionally, tackling below the waist was legalized, and a static line of scrimmage was instituted.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Despite these new rules, football remained a violent sport.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Dangerous mass-formations like the flying wedge resulted in serious injuries and deaths.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A 1905 peak of 19 fatalities nationwide resulted in a threat by President Theodore Roosevelt to abolish the game unless major changes were made.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In response, 62 colleges and universities met in New York City to discuss rule changes on December 28, 1905.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] These proceedings resulted in the formation of the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States, later renamed the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The legal forward pass was introduced in 1906, although its effect was initially minimal due to the restrictions placed on its use.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The idea of a 40-yard-wider field was opposed by Harvard due to the size of the new Harvard Stadium.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Other rule changes introduced that year included the reduction of playing time from 70 to 60 minutes and an increase of the distance required for a first down from 5 to 10 yards (4.6 to 9.1 m).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] To reduce infighting and dirty play between teams, the neutral zone was created along the width of the football before the snap.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Scoring was also adjusted: points awarded for field goals were reduced to three in 1909 and points for touchdowns were raised to six in 1912.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Also in 1912, the field was shortened to 100 yards (91 m) long, two 10-yard-long (9.1 m) end zones were created, and teams were given four downs instead of three to advance the ball 10 yards (9.1 m).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The roughing the passer penalty was implemented in 1914, and eligible players were first allowed to catch the ball anywhere on the field in 1918.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] On November 12, 1892, Pudge Heffelfinger was paid $500 (equivalent to $17,917 in 2025) to play a game for the Allegheny Athletic Association against the Pittsburgh Athletic Club.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Despite these extra benefits, the game had a strict sense of amateurism at the time, and direct payment to players was frowned upon, if not prohibited outright.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Over time, professional play became increasingly common, and with it came rising salaries and unpredictable player movement, as well as the illegal payment of college players who were still in school.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The National Football League (NFL), a group of professional teams that was originally established in 1920 as the American Professional Football Association, aimed to solve these problems.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] This new league's stated goals included an end to bidding wars over players, prevention of the use of college players, and abolition of the practice of paying players to leave another team.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] By 1922, the NFL had established itself as America's premier professional football league.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The dominant form of football at the time was played at the collegiate level.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The upstart NFL received a boost to its legitimacy in 1925, however, when an NFL team, the Pottsville Maroons, defeated a team of Notre Dame all-stars in an exhibition game.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A greater emphasis on the passing game helped professional football to distinguish itself further from the college game during the late 1930s.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Football, in general, became increasingly popular following the 1958 NFL Championship game between the Baltimore Colts and the New York Giants, still referred to as the "Greatest Game Ever Played".
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The game, a 23–17 overtime victory by the Colts, was seen by millions of television viewers and had a major influence on the popularity of the sport.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] By the mid-1960s, football was the most popular sport in the United States.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In 1972, polling from Gallup, Inc. found that twice as many Americans identified football as their favorite sport (38%) as compared to baseball (19%); the sport has remained the most popular in the United States since.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In 1960, the American Football League (AFL) was created to compete with the NFL.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The AFL began in relative obscurity but eventually thrived, with an initial television contract with the ABC television network.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The AFL's existence forced the conservative NFL to expand to Dallas and Minnesota in an attempt to destroy the new league.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Meanwhile, the AFL introduced many new features to professional football in the United States and actively recruited minority players.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The AFL also signed several star college players who had also been drafted by NFL teams.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Competition for players heated up in 1965, when the AFL New York Jets signed rookie Joe Namath to a then-record $437,000 contract (equivalent to $4.46 million in 2024).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A five-year, $40 million NBC television contract followed, which helped to sustain the young league.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The bidding war for players ended in 1966 when NFL owners approached the AFL regarding a merger, and the two leagues agreed on one that took full effect in 1970.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] This agreement provided for a common draft that would take place each year, and it instituted an annual World Championship game to be played between the champions of each league.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] This championship game, which would come to be known as the Super Bowl, began play at the end of the 1966 season.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Once the merger was completed, it was no longer a championship game between two leagues, instead being competed between the American Football Conference (AFC) and the National Football Conference (NFC).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Prior to the 1956 college football season, NCAA schools were organized into an upper University Division and lower College Division.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In the summer of 1973, the University Division became Division I, but by 1976, there was a desire to further separate the major football programs from those that were less financially successful, while still allowing their other sports to compete at the top level.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In 1978, the NCAA divided Division I football into two subdivisions: NCAA Division I-A (known today as the Football Bowl Subdivision, or FBS) and Division I-AA (known today as the Football Championship Subdivision, or FCS).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The FCS adopted a single-elimination playoff structure to determine its champion, while the FBS retained its tradition of postseason bowl games.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Each bowl game was associated with a particular conference, and earning a spot in a major bowl game was the reward for winning a conference.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] This arrangement was beneficial to both conferences and bowl games, but it generally prevented the top-ranked teams from meeting in a true national championship game.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Because the NCAA itself does not officially sanction a Division I-FBS national champion, FBS national champions prior to 1992 were determined by polls, which frequently led to controversial or "split" national champions.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In 1992, the Bowl Coalition was created to determine the national champion.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] It was replaced in 1995 by the Bowl Alliance, which itself gave way to the Bowl Championship Series (BCS) in 1997.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] All three of these systems consisted of a single national championship game, as well as a set of other major bowl games.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In 2014, the BCS was replaced by the College Football Playoff (CFP), a single-elimination tournament.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In another major change, in 2021, following legal pressure and antitrust lawsuits, the NCAA and its conferences began allowing schools to offer compensation to student athletes for the use of their names, images, and likenesses (NIL).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] NCAA* allowed schools to directly pay players, ending the traditionally amateur nature of college athletics in the United States.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A football game is played between two teams of 11 players each.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Playing with more on the field is punishable by a penalty.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Teams may substitute any number of their players between downs; this "platoon" system has resulted in teams utilizing specialized offensive, defensive and special teams units.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The number of players allowed on an active roster varies by league; the NFL has a 53-man roster, while NCAA Division I allows teams to have up to 105 players on their roster.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Individual players in a football game must be designated with a uniform number between 0 and 99.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] NFL teams are required to number their players by a league-approved numbering system, and any exceptions must be approved by the commissioner.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] NCAA and NFHS teams are "strongly advised" to number their offensive players according to a league-suggested numbering scheme.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Women are eligible to play in high school, college, and professional football, but most football players are men.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] No woman has ever played in the NFL, but women have played in high school and college football games.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In 2018, women and girls comprised 0.5% of players in Pop Warner Little Scholars youth football, 0.2% of players in high school football, and 10.9% of Americans who report playing tackle football.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The role of the offensive unit is to advance the football down the field with the ultimate goal of scoring a touchdown.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The offensive team must line up in a legal formation before they can snap the ball.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] An offensive formation is considered illegal if there are more than four players in the backfield or fewer than five players numbered 50–79 on the offensive line.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Players can line up temporarily in a position whose eligibility is different from what their number permits as long as they report the change immediately to the referee, who then informs the defensive team of the change.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Neither team's players, except the center (C), are allowed to line up in or cross the neutral zone until the ball is snapped.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Interior offensive linemen are not allowed to move until the snap of the ball.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The main backfield positions are the quarterback (QB), running back (RB), and fullback (FB).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The quarterback is the leader of the offense.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Either the quarterback or a coach calls the plays.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Quarterbacks typically inform the rest of the offense of the play in the huddle before the team lines up.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The quarterback lines up behind the center to take the snap and then hands the ball off, throws it, or runs with it.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The primary role of the running back is to carry the ball on running plays.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Fullbacks tend to be larger than halfbacks and function primarily as blockers, but they are sometimes used as runners in short-yardage or goal-line situations.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The offensive line (OL) consists of several players whose primary function is to block members of the defensive line from tackling the ball carrier on running plays or sacking the quarterback on passing plays.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The most important role on the offensive line is the center, who is not just responsible for blocking and snapping the ball, but also for handling line adjustments and pre-snap strategy.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] On either side of the center are the guards (G), while tackles (T) line up outside the guards.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The principal receivers are the wide receivers (WR) and the tight ends (TE).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Wide receivers line up on or near the line of scrimmage, split outside the line.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The main goal of the wide receiver is to catch passes thrown by the quarterback, but they may also function as decoys or as blockers during running plays.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Tight ends line up next to the offensive line and function both as receivers and as blockers.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The role of the defense is to prevent the offense from scoring by tackling the ball carrier or by forcing turnovers.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Turnovers include interceptions (a defender catching a forward pass intended for the offense) and forced fumbles (taking possession of the ball from the ball-carrier).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The defensive line (DL) consists of defensive ends (DE) and defensive tackles (DT).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Defensive ends line up on the ends of the defensive line, while defensive tackles line up on the inside, between the defensive ends.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The primary responsibilities of defensive ends and defensive tackles are to stop running plays on the outside and inside, respectively, to pressure the quarterback on passing plays, and to occupy the line so that the linebackers can break through.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Linebackers line up behind the defensive line but in front of the defensive backfield.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] They are divided into two types: middle linebackers (MLB) and outside linebackers (OLB).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Linebackers tend to serve as the defensive leaders and call the defensive plays, given their vantage point of the offensive backfield.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Their roles include defending the run, pressuring the quarterback, and tackling backs, wide receivers, and tight ends.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The defensive backfield, often called the secondary, consists of cornerbacks (CB) and safeties (S).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties are themselves divided into free safeties (FS) and strong safeties (SS).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Cornerbacks line up outside the defensive formation, typically opposite a receiver to be able to cover them.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties line up between the cornerbacks but farther back in the secondary.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties tend to be viewed as "the last line of defense" and are responsible for stopping deep passing plays as well as breakout running plays.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The special teams unit is responsible for all kicking plays.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The special teams unit of the team in control of the ball tries to execute field goal (FG) attempts, punts, and kickoffs, while the opposing team's unit will aim to block or return them.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Three positions are specific to the field goal and PAT (point after touchdown) unit: the placekicker (K or PK), holder (H), and long snapper (LS).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The long snapper's job is to snap the football to the holder, who will catch and place it on the ground for the kicker.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] There is usually never a holder on kickoffs, because the ball is kicked off a tee; however, a holder may be used in certain situations, such as if wind is preventing the ball from remaining upright on the tee.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The player on the receiving team who catches the ball is known as the kick returner (KR).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The positions specific to punt plays are the punter (P), long snapper, upback, and gunner.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The long snapper snaps the football directly to the punter, who then drops and kicks it before it hits the ground.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Gunners line up split outside the line and race down the field, aiming to tackle the punt returner (PR)—the player who catches the punt.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Upbacks line up a short distance, typically 1-7 yards, behind the line of scrimmage, providing additional protection to the punter.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In football, the winner is the team that has scored more points at the end of the game.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] There are multiple ways to score in a football game.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The touchdown (TD), worth six points, is the most valuable scoring play.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A touchdown is scored when a live ball is advanced into, caught, or recovered in the opposing team's end zone.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The scoring team then attempts a try, more commonly known as the point(s)-after-touchdown (PAT) or conversion, which is a single scoring opportunity.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by a place kick or drop kick through the goal posts, it is worth one point, typically called the extra point.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by what would normally be a touchdown, it is worth two points; this is known as a two-point conversion.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In general, the extra point is almost always successful, while the two-point conversion is a much riskier play with a higher probability of failure; accordingly, extra point attempts are far more common than two-point conversion attempts.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A field goal (FG), worth three points, is scored when the ball is place kicked or drop kicked through the uprights and over the crossbars of the defense's goalposts.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Almost all field goal attempts are done via place kick.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] While drop kicks were common in the early days of the sport, the shape of modern footballs makes it difficult to reliably drop kick the ball.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The last successful scoring play by drop kick in the NFL was accomplished in 2006; prior to that, the last successful drop kick had been made in 1941.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] After a PAT attempt or successful field goal, the scoring team must kick the ball off to the other team.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A safety is scored when the ball carrier is tackled in the carrier's own end zone.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties are worth two points, which are awarded to the defense.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In addition, the team that conceded the safety must kick the ball to the scoring team via a free kick.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties are the least common method of scoring in football.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Football games are played on a rectangular field that measures 120 yards (110 m) long and 53+1⁄3 yards (48.8 m) wide.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Lines marked along the ends and sides of the field are known as the end lines and sidelines.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Goal lines are marked 10 yards (9.1 m) inward from each end line.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Weighted pylons are placed along each sideline, on the inside corner of the intersections with the goal lines and end lines.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] White markings on the field identify the distance from the end zone.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Inbound lines, or hash marks, are short parallel lines that mark off 1-yard (0.91 m) increments.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Yard lines, which can run the width of the field, are marked every 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A one-yard-wide line is placed at each end of the field; this line is marked at the center of the two-yard line in professional play and at the three-yard line in college play.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Numerals that display the distance from the closest goal line in yards are placed on both sides of the field every ten yards.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Goalposts are located at the center of the plane of the two end lines.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The crossbar of these posts is 10 feet (3.0 m) above the ground, with vertical uprights at the end of the crossbar 18 feet 6 inches (5.64 m) apart for professional and collegiate play, and 23 feet 4 inches (7.11 m) apart for high school play.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The uprights extend vertically 35 feet (11 m) on professional fields, a minimum of 10 yards (9.1 m) on college fields, and a minimum of 10 feet (3.0 m) on high school fields.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Goal posts are padded at the base, and orange ribbons are normally placed at the tip of each upright as indicators of wind strength and direction.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The football itself is a prolate spheroid leather ball, similar to the balls used in rugby or Australian rules football.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] At all levels of play, the football is inflated to 12+1⁄2 to 13+1⁄2 psi (86 to 93 kPa), or just under one atmosphere, and weighs 14 to 15 ounces (400 to 430 g); beyond that, the exact dimensions vary slightly.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In professional play the ball has a long axis of 11 to 11+1⁄4 inches (28 to 29 cm), a long circumference of 28 to 28+1⁄2 inches (71 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 21 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In college and high school play the ball has a long axis of 10+7⁄8 to 11+7⁄16 inches (27.6 to 29.1 cm), a long circumference of 27+3⁄4 to 28+1⁄2 inches (70 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 20+3⁄4 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Football games last for a total of 60 minutes in professional and college play and are divided into two halves of 30 minutes and four quarters of 15 minutes.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] High school football games are 48 minutes in length with two halves of 24 minutes and four quarters of 12 minutes.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The two halves are separated by a halftime period, and the first and third quarters are followed by a short break.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Before the game starts, the referee and each team's captain meet at midfield for a coin toss.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The visiting team can call either "heads" or "tails"; the winner of the toss chooses whether to receive or kick off the ball or which goal they wish to defend.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] They can defer their choice until the second half.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Unless the winning team decides to defer, the losing team chooses the option the winning team did not select—to receive, kick, or select a goal to defend to begin the second half.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Most teams choose to receive or defer, because choosing to kick the ball to start the game allows the other team to choose which goal to defend.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Teams switch goals following the first and third quarters.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] If a down is in progress when a quarter ends, play continues until the down is completed.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] If certain fouls are committed during play while time has expired, the quarter may be extended through an untimed down.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Games last longer than their defined length due to play stoppages—the average NFL game lasts slightly over three hours.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Time in a football game is measured by the game clock.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] An operator is responsible for starting, stopping and operating the game clock based on the direction of the appropriate official.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A separate play clock is used to show the amount of time within which the offense must initiate a play.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The play clock is set to 25 seconds after certain administrative stoppages in play and to 40 seconds when play is proceeding without such stoppages.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] If the offense fails to start a play before the play clock reads "00", a delay of game foul is called on the offense.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] There are two main ways the offense can advance the ball: running and passing.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In a typical play, the center passes the ball backwards and between their legs to the quarterback in a process known as the snap.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The quarterback then either hands the ball off to a running back, throws the ball, or runs with it.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The play ends when the player with the ball is tackled or goes out-of-bounds or a pass hits the ground without a player having caught it.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A forward pass can be legally attempted only if the passer is behind the line of scrimmage; only one forward pass can be attempted per down.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] As in rugby, players can also pass the ball backwards at any point during a play.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In the NFL, a down also ends immediately if the runner's helmet comes off.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The offense is given a series of four plays, known as downs.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] If the offense advances ten or more yards in the four downs, they are awarded a new set of four downs.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] If they fail to advance ten yards, possession of the football is turned over to the defense.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] In most situations, if the offense reaches their fourth down they will punt the ball to the other team, which forces them to begin their drive from farther down the field; if they are in field goal range, they might attempt to score a field goal instead.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A group of officials, the chain crew, keeps track of both the downs and the distance measurements.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The spot needed to secure a first down is known as the line to gain.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] On television, a yellow line is electronically superimposed on the field to show the line to gain to the viewing audience.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] There are two categories of kicks in football: scrimmage kicks, which can be executed by the offensive team on any down from behind or on the line of scrimmage, and free kicks.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The free kicks are the kickoff, which starts the first and third quarters and overtime and follows a try attempt or a successful field goal, and the safety kick, which follows a safety.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] On a kickoff, the ball is placed at the 35-yard line of the kicking team in professional and college play and at the 40-yard line in high school play.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The ball may be drop kicked or place kicked.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] If a place kick is chosen, the ball can be placed on the ground or a tee; a holder may be used in either case.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] On a safety kick, the kicking team kicks the ball from their own 20-yard line.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] They can punt, drop kick or place kick the ball, but a tee may not be used in professional play.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Any member of the receiving team may catch or advance the ball.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The ball may be recovered by the kicking team once it has gone at least ten yards and has touched the ground or has been touched by any member of the receiving team.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The three types of scrimmage kicks are place kicks, drop kicks, and punts.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Only place kicks and drop kicks can score points.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The place kick is the standard method used to score points, because the pointy shape of the football makes it difficult to reliably drop kick.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Once the ball has been kicked from a scrimmage kick, it can be advanced by the kicking team only if it is caught or recovered behind the line of scrimmage.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] If it is touched or recovered by the kicking team beyond this line, it becomes dead at the spot where it was touched.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The kicking team is prohibited from interfering with the receiver's opportunity to catch the ball.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The receiving team has the option of signaling for a fair catch, which prohibits the defense from blocking into or tackling the receiver.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The play ends as soon as the ball is caught, and the ball may not be advanced.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Officials are responsible for enforcing game rules and monitoring the clock.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] All officials carry a whistle and wear black-and-white striped shirts and black hats, except for the referee, whose hat is white.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Each carries a weighted yellow flag that is thrown to the ground to signal that a foul has been called.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] An official who spots multiple fouls will throw their hat as a secondary signal.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Women can serve as officials; Sarah Thomas became the NFL's first female official in 2015.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Another set of officials, the chain crew, are responsible for moving the chains.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The chains, consisting of two large sticks with a 10-yard-long chain between them, are used to measure for a first down.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The chain crew stays on the sidelines during the game, but if requested by the officials, they will briefly bring the chains onto the field to measure.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A typical chain crew will have at least three people—two members of the chain crew will hold either of the two sticks, while a third will hold the down marker.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The down marker, a large stick with a dial on it, is flipped after each play to indicate the current down and is typically moved to the approximate spot of the ball.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The chain crew system has been used for over 100 years and is considered an accurate measure of distance, rarely subject to criticism from either side.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Football is a full-contact sport, and injuries are relatively common.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur during training sessions, particularly ones that involve contact between players.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] To try to prevent injuries, players are required to wear a set of equipment.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] At a minimum players must wear a football helmet and a set of shoulder pads, but individual leagues may require additional padding such as thigh pads and guards, knee pads, chest protectors, and mouthguards.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur in the lower extremities, particularly in the knee, but a significant number also affect the upper extremities.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] The most common types of injuries are strains, sprains, bruises, fractures, dislocations, and concussions.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Repeated concussions (and possibly sub-concussive head impacts) can increase a person's risk in later life for CTE (chronic traumatic encephalopathy) and health issues such as dementia, Parkinson's disease, and depression.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Concussions are often caused by helmet-to-helmet or upper-body contact between opposing players, although helmets have prevented more serious injuries such as skull fractures.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] However, a study in the *Orthopaedic Journal of Sports Medicine* found that Heads Up Football was ineffective; the same study noted that more extensive reforms implemented by Pop Warner Little Scholars and its member teams were effective in significantly reducing concussion rates.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] A 2018 study performed by the VA Boston Healthcare System and the Boston University School of Medicine found that tackle football before age 12 was correlated with earlier onset of symptoms of CTE, but not with increased symptom severity.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] More specifically, each year a player played tackle football under age 12 predicted earlier onset of cognitive, behavioral, and mood problems by an average of two and a half years.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] To help mitigate injuries, the NCAA recommends limiting full contact (tackling to the ground) practices, avoiding full contact on consecutive days, and no more than 20 hours of practice per week.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p01] Players must receive one day off per week.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The National Football League (NFL) and the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) are the most popular football leagues in the United States.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The National Football League was founded in 1920 and has since become the largest and most popular sport in the United States.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL has the highest average attendance of any sporting league in the world, with an average attendance of 66,960 during the 2011 NFL season.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL championship game is called the Super Bowl, and is among the biggest events in club sports worldwide.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] It is played between the champions of the National Football Conference (NFC) and the American Football Conference (AFC), and its winner is awarded the Vince Lombardi Trophy.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] College football is the third-most popular sport in the United States, behind professional football and professional baseball, respectively.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The NCAA, the largest collegiate organization, is divided into three Divisions: Division I, Division II and Division III.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Division I is the highest level of play, while Division III is the lowest; Division I and II programs can offer athletic scholarships to student-athletes, while Division III programs cannot.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Division I football is further divided into two subdivisions: the Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS) and the Football Championship Subdivision (FCS).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The champions of each level of play are determined through playoff systems.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Other national college football organizations include the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA), which comprises around 90 smaller colleges, and the National Junior College Athletic Association (NJCAA), whose membership consists of two-year colleges.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] High school football is the most popular sport in the United States played by boys.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The NFHS is the largest organization for high school football, with member associations in all 50 states as well as the District of Columbia.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] USA Football is the governing body for youth and amateur football, and Pop Warner Little Scholars is the largest organization for youth football.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The most successful league to directly compete with the NFL was the American Football League (AFL), which existed from 1960 to 1969.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The AFL became a significant rival in 1964 before signing a five-year, US$36 million television deal with NBC.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] AFL teams began signing NFL players to contracts, and the league's popularity grew to challenge that of the NFL.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged in the 1970 season, and all the AFL teams joined the NFL.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] An earlier league, the All-America Football Conference (AAFC), was in play from 1946 to 1949.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] After it had dissolved, two AAFC teams, the Cleveland Browns and the San Francisco 49ers, became members of the NFL; another member, the Baltimore Colts joined the league, but folded after just a year in the NFL.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Other attempts to start rival leagues since the AFL merged with the NFL in 1970 have been far less successful, as professional football salaries and the NFL's television contracts began to escalate out of the reach of competitors and the NFL covered more of the larger cities.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The World Football League (WFL) played for two seasons, in 1974 and 1975, but faced such severe monetary issues it could not pay its players.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] In its second and final season the WFL attempted to establish a stable credit rating, but the league disbanded before the season could be completed.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The United States Football League (USFL) operated for three seasons from 1983 to 1985.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Originally not intended as a rival league, the entry of owners who sought marquee talent and to challenge the NFL led to an escalation in salaries and ensuing financial losses.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] A subsequent US$1.5 billion antitrust lawsuit against the NFL was successful in court, but the league was awarded only $1 in damages, which was automatically tripled to $3 under antitrust law.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The original XFL, created in 2001 by WWE co-founder Vince McMahon, lasted for only one season.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Despite television contracts with NBC and UPN, and high expectations, the XFL suffered from low quality of play and poor reception for its use of tawdry professional wrestling gimmicks, which caused initially high ratings and attendance to collapse.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The United Football League (UFL) began in 2009 but folded after suspending its 2012 season after having lost $120 million over just three seasons.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Another spring league, the Alliance of American Football lasted less than one season, unable to keep investors.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] A revived United States Football League began play in 2022 and quickly faced immediate competition from the XFL, which resumed play in 2023.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged following the 2023 season, forming a new United Football League (UFL).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] American football leagues exist throughout the world, but the game has yet to achieve the international success and popularity of baseball and basketball.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] At the international level, Canada, Mexico, and Japan are considered to be second-tier, while Austria, Germany, and France would rank among a third tier.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] These countries rank far below the United States, which is dominant at the international level.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] NFL Europa, the developmental league of the NFL, operated from 1991 to 1992 and then from 1995 to 2007.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] At the time of its closure, NFL Europa had five teams based in Germany and one in the Netherlands.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] In Germany, the German Football League (GFL) has 16 teams and has operated for over 40 seasons, with the league's championship game, the German Bowl, closing out each season.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The league operates in a promotion and relegation structure with German Football League 2 (GFL2), which also has 16 teams.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The United Kingdom also operated several teams within NFL Europe during the League's tenure.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The resulting rise in popularity of the sport brought the NFL back to the country in 2007 where they now hold the NFL International Series in London, currently consisting of four regular season games.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The continuing interest and growth in both the sport and the series has led to the possible formation of a potential NFL franchise in London.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] NFL commissioner Roger Goodell aims to host 16 international games each year, enough for each NFL team to play one international game each year.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom, the British American Football Association National Leagues (BAFANL), an amateur competition, is the top level of American football.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Teams compete across multiple levels in a promotion and relegation structure; the league's championship is the Britbowl.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] University competition is held through the British Universities American Football League (BUAFL), which was formed in 2007.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] In 2008, the league launched a partnership with the NFL, through its partner organization NFL UK.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] From 2007 to 2014, the BUAFL grew from 42 teams and 2,460 participants to 75 teams and over 4,100 people involved.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The standard form of American football is not an Olympic sport, but it was a demonstration sport at the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The International Federation of American Football (IFAF), an international governing body composed of continental federations, received provisional recognition from the International Olympic Committee (IOC) in 2014 and was fully recognized by the IOC in 2015.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] American football federations are present in Africa, the Americas, Asia, Europe, and Oceania; a total of 75 national football federations exist as of 2023.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The IFAF runs tournaments such as the IFAF World Championship, the IFAF Women's World Championship, the IFAF Junior World Championship, and the Flag Football World Championship.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Obstacles towards the goal of becoming an Olympic sport included the predominant participation of men in international play and the short three-week Olympic schedule.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Large team sizes were an additional difficulty, due to the Olympics' set limit of 10,500 athletes and coaches.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] American football also faced an issue with a lack of global visibility.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Nigel Melville, the CEO of USA Rugby, noted that "American football is recognized globally as a sport, but it's not played globally." To solve these concerns, major effort was put into promoting flag football, a modified version of American football, at the international level.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Flag football for men and women will debut as an Olympic sport at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] "Baseball is still called the national pastime, but football is by far the more popular sport in American society", according to ESPN.com's Sean McAdam.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] In a 2014 poll conducted by Harris Interactive, professional football ranked as the most popular sport, and college football ranked third behind only professional football and baseball; 46% of participants ranked some form of the game as their favorite sport.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Professional football has ranked as the most popular sport in the poll since 1985, when it surpassed baseball for the first time.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Professional football is most popular among those who live in the eastern United States and rural areas, while college football is most popular in the southern United States and among people with graduate and post-graduate degrees.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Football is also the most-played sport by high school and college athletes in the United States.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] A 2022 survey from National Football Foundation found that one million high-school athletes played the sport, with another 81,000 college athletes across both the NCAA and the NAIA.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The Super Bowl is the most popular single-day sporting event in the United States, and is among the biggest club sporting events in the world in terms of TV viewership.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL made approximately $12 billion in revenue in 2022.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Super Bowl games account for eight of the top ten most-watched broadcasts in American history; Super Bowl LVII, played on February 12, 2023, was watched by a record 115.1 million Americans, and is second only to the Apollo 11 moon landing (125 million viewers).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL is the most valuable sports league in the world, with the average team valued at over $8 billion.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] American football also plays a significant role in American culture.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The day on which the Super Bowl is held is considered a *de facto* national holiday, and in parts of the country like Texas, the sport has been compared to a religion.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Football is also linked to other holidays; New Year's Day is traditionally the date for several college football bowl games, including the Rose Bowl.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] However, if New Year's Day is on a Sunday, the bowl games are moved to another date so as not to conflict with the typical NFL Sunday schedule.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Thanksgiving football is another American tradition, hosting many high school, college, and professional games.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Implicit rules such as playing through pain and sacrificing for the better of the team are promoted in football culture.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] In Canada, the game has a significant following.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] According to a 2013 poll, 21% of respondents said they followed the NFL "very closely" or "fairly closely", making it the third-most followed league behind the National Hockey League (NHL) and Canadian Football League (CFL).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] American football also has a long history in Mexico, which was introduced to the sport in 1896.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] It was the second-most popular sport in Mexico in the 1950s, with the game being particularly popular in colleges.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The *Los Angeles Times* notes the NFL claims over 16 million fans in Mexico, which places the country third behind the U.S. and Canada.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] American football is played in Mexico both professionally and as part of the college sports system.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] A professional league, the Liga de Fútbol Americano Profesional (LFA), was founded in 2016.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Japan was introduced to the sport in 1934 by Paul Rusch, a teacher and Christian missionary who helped to establish football teams at three universities in Tokyo.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Play was halted during World War II by order of Emperor Hirohito, but the sport began growing in popularity again after the war.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] As of 2010, there are more than 400 high school football teams in Japan, with over 15,000 participants, and over 100 teams play in the Kantoh Collegiate Football Association (KCFA).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The X-League is the largest American football league in Japan, and the largest American football league in the world to use a promotion-relegation system.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Some teams in the X-League, like the Panasonic Impulse, are sponsored by corporations, and all Japanese players on these teams are employed by the corporation.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The league operates in separate spring and fall seasons, with each team playing five games.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The top eight teams make the playoffs, which are played in Tokyo Dome; the champion is determined by the Rice Bowl.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Europe is a major target for the expansion of the game by football organizers.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom in the 1980s, the sport was popular, with the 1986 Super Bowl being watched by over four million people (about 1 out of every 14 Britons).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Its popularity faded during the 1990s, coinciding with the establishment of the Premier League—the top level of the English association football (soccer) league system.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] According to BBC America, there is a "social stigma" surrounding American football in the UK, with many Brits feeling the sport has no right to call itself "football" due to the lack of emphasis on kicking.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Nonetheless, the sport has retained a following in the United Kingdom; the NFL operates a media network in the country, and since 2007 has hosted the NFL International Series in London.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Super Bowl viewership has also rebounded, with over 4.4 million Britons watching Super Bowl XLVI.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The sport is played in European countries like Switzerland, which has American football clubs in every major city, and Germany, where the sport has around 45,000 registered amateur players.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] It was generally unknown there until the 1980s when a small group of players began playing on Copacabana Beach in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The sport grew gradually with 700 amateur players registering within 20 years.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Games were played on the beach with modified rules and without the traditional football equipment due to its lack of availability in Brazil.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Eventually, a tournament, the Carioca championship, was founded, with the championship Carioca Bowl played to determine a league champion.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The country saw its first full-pad game of football in October 2008.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] According to *The Rio Times*, the sport is one of the fastest-growing sports in Brazil and is almost as commonly played as soccer on the beaches of Copacabana and Botafogo.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Football in Brazil is governed by the Confederação Brasileira de Futebol Americano (CBFA), which had over 5,000 registered players as of November 2013.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The sport's increase in popularity has been attributed to games aired on ESPN, which began airing in Brazil in 1992 with Portuguese commentary.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The popularity and "easy accessibility" of non-contact versions of the sport in Brazil has led to a rise in participation by female players.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] According to ESPN, the American football audience in Brazil increased 800% between 2013 and 2016.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The network, along with Esporte Interativo, airs games there on cable television.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] NFL had expressed interest in having games in the country, eventually resulting in São Paulo's Arena Corinthians hosting Brazil's first NFL game in 2024, and the Super Bowl has become a widely watched event in Brazil at bars and movie theaters.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Further countries have also expressed interest in football to a lesser degree.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The Arab world has expressed growing interest in American football, with many countries in the region being members of IFAF Asia.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Jordan and the United Arab Emirates, which are not members of IFAF, have established their own domestic leagues.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Egypt established two leagues for the sport, namely the Egyptian League of American Football and the Egyptian Federation of American Football, and Saudi Arabia hosts two teams based out of Jeddah and Yanbu respectively.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] China has additionally been a target for the expansion of the sport, with the Mainland being the home of the Chinese National Football League as well as a growing audience of Super Bowl watchers.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Three franchises are also based out of Hong Kong, which prior to the COVID-19 pandemic regularly played mainland teams.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] NFL games average 900,000 viewers in China, though the league has cited logistical challenges which would prevent teams from playing games akin to abroad games in European countries.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Canadian football, the predominant form of football in Canada, is closely related to American football—both sports developed from rugby and are considered to be the chief variants of gridiron football.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The Canadian Football League (CFL) is the major Canadian league and is the second-most popular sporting league in Canada, behind the National Hockey League.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Football Canada is the governing body for amateur Canadian football, and is also member of the International Federation of American Football.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] NFL players have played in the CFL and vice versa; quarterback Warren Moon is the only player in both Canadian Football Hall of Fame and the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL and CFL had a formal working relationship from 1997 to 2006.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The CFL has a strategic partnership with two American football leagues, the German Football League (GFL) and the Liga de Futbol Americano Profesional (LFA).
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Rule changes announced in 2025 by the CFL will bring some elements of the sport closer to those of American football, while retaining the larger number of players, wider field, and three-down limit.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The Indoor Football League is an example of a prominent indoor league.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] The Arena Football League, which was founded in 1987 and ceased operations in 2019, was one of the longest-lived indoor football leagues.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] In 2004, the league was called "America's fifth major sport" by *ESPN The Magazine*.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Some schools that lack the enrollment numbers to run a competitive 11-man team choose to play nine-man, eight-man, or six-man football, which utilize modified rules to account for smaller team sizes.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] There are several non-contact variants of football, such as flag football.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] In flag football the ball-carrier is not tackled; instead, defenders aim to pull a flag tied around the ball-carrier's waist.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Flag football has become increasingly popular due to its lower likelihood of head injuries and its openness to female athletes; according to the NFL, which promotes flag football through NFL Flag, roughly 25% of flag football players are women and girls.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Another variant, touch football, simply requires the ball-carrier to be touched to be considered downed.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Depending on the rules used, a game of touch football may require the ball-carrier be touched with either one or two hands to be considered downed.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Wheelchair football is a parasport adapting the rules of football for people with physical disabilities.
[src:road-sports/american-football-p02] Although it uses touch rules instead of tackling, wheelchair football isn't a non-contact sport; participants engage in both "big hits" and "physical blocks".
[src:road-sports/armed-forces-classic] The **Armed Forces Classic** is a college basketball event operated on a military boatcraft, televised on ESPN, that involves one or two games played in front of military members and their families.
[src:road-sports/armed-forces-classic] The first Armed Forces Classic was held on November 9, 2012, between Michigan State and UConn, at the Ramstein Air Base in Germany.
[src:road-sports/armed-forces-classic] It was the first college basketball game played between two NCAA Division I teams in Europe.
[src:road-sports/armed-forces-classic] The 2016 edition broke new ground for the event in several respects.
[src:road-sports/armed-forces-classic] It was the first to feature two games, and also the first not to be played at a military base, with games held at Stan Sheriff Center on the campus of the University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa in Honolulu.
[src:road-sports/armed-forces-classic] Additionally, it was the first time tickets were sold to the general public, although all seats in the arena's lower bowl were reserved for military personnel and their families.
[src:road-sports/armed-forces-classic] The event was held in Honolulu to commemorate the 75th anniversary of the attack on Pearl Harbor; surrounding events were held at Joint Base Pearl Harbor–Hickam.
[src:road-sports/armed-forces-classic] The game was cancelled in 2020 and 2021 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:road-sports/armed-forces-classic] Sites for future games are tentative and may change due to military circumstances.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The objective of the game is to score more goals than the opposing team by moving the ball beyond the goal line into a rectangular-framed goal defended by the opponent.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Traditionally, the game has been played over two 45-minute halves, for a total match time of 90 minutes.
[src:road-sports/association-football] With an estimated 250 million players active in over 200 countries and territories, it is the world's most popular sport.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Association football is played in accordance with the Laws of the Game, a set of rules that has been in effect since 1863 and maintained by the International Football Association Board (IFAB) since 1886.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The game is played with a football that is 68–70 cm (27–28 in) in circumference.
[src:road-sports/association-football] When the ball is in play, the players mainly use their feet, but may also use any other part of their body, except for their hands or arms, to control, strike, or pass the ball; the head, chest, and thighs are commonly used.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Only the goalkeepers may use their hands and arms, but only within their own penalty area.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Depending on the format of the competition, an equal number of goals scored may result in a draw being declared with 1 point awarded to each team, or the game may go into extra time or a penalty shoot-out.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Internationally, association football is governed by FIFA.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Under FIFA, there are six continental confederations: AFC, CAF, CONCACAF, CONMEBOL, OFC, and UEFA.
[src:road-sports/association-football] National associations (e.g. the FA in England, U.S.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Soccer in the United States, etc.) are responsible for managing the game in their own countries both professionally and at an amateur level, and coordinating competitions in accordance with the Laws of the Game.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The most prestigious senior international competition is the FIFA World Cup.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The men's World Cup is the most-viewed sporting event in the world, surpassing the Olympic Games.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The most prestigious competition in European club football is the UEFA Champions League, which attracts an extensive television audience worldwide.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The final of the men's Champions League is the most-watched annual sporting event in the world.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Association football is part of a family of football games that emerged from various ball games played worldwide since antiquity.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The word "association" in this term refers to the Football Association (the FA), founded in London in 1863, which published the first set of rules for the sport that same year.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The term was coined to distinguish the type of football played in accordance with the FA rules from other types that were gaining popularity at the time, particularly rugby football.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The term *soccer* comes from Oxford "-er" slang, which was prevalent at the University of Oxford in England from about 1875, and is thought to have been borrowed from the slang of Rugby School.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Initially spelt *assoccer* (a shortening of "association"), it was later reduced to the modern spelling.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Early alternative spellings included *socca* and *socker*.
[src:road-sports/association-football] This form of slang also gave rise to *rugger* for rugby football, *fiver* and *tenner* for five pound and ten pound notes, and the now-archaic *footer* that was also a name for association football.
[src:road-sports/association-football] A notable exception is New Zealand, where in the first two decades of the 21st century, under the influence of international television, "football" has been gaining prevalence, despite the dominance of other types of football, namely rugby union and rugby league.
[src:road-sports/association-football] FIFA has stated that soccer originated in Britain, starting around the eighth century, and that no historical connection exists with any game played in antiquity outside Europe.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The modern rules of association football are based on the mid-19th century efforts to standardise the widely varying forms of football played in the public schools of England.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Kicking ball games arose independently multiple times across multiple cultures.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The Chinese competitive game **cuju** (蹴鞠, literally "kickball"; also known as *tsu chu*) resembles modern association football as well as a mix of basketball and volleyball.
[src:road-sports/association-football] This is the earliest form of a kicking game for which there is historical evidence.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The game was first recorded as in exercise in the Zhan Guo Ce, a military history from the Han dynasty.
[src:road-sports/association-football] **Cuju** players would pass the ball around, having to avoid it touching the ground at any point.
[src:road-sports/association-football] It was then passed to a designated player, who attempted to kick it through the *fengliu yan*, a circular goal atop 10–11 meter poles.
[src:road-sports/association-football] During the Han dynasty (206 BCE – 220 CE), **cuju** games were standardised and rules were established.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The Silk Road facilitated the transmission of *cuju* outside of China, especially the form of the game popular in the Tang dynasty, the period when the inflatable ball was invented and replaced the stuffed ball.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Other East Asian games include **kemari** in Japan and **chuk-guk** in Korea, both influenced by *cuju*.
[src:road-sports/association-football] **Kemari** originated after the year 600 during the Asuka period.
[src:road-sports/association-football] It was a ceremonial rather than a competitive game, and involved the kicking of a *mari*, a ball made of animal skin.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In North America, *pasuckuakohowog* was a ball game played by the Algonquians; it was described as "almost identical to the kind of folk football being played in Europe at the same time, in which the ball was kicked through goals".
[src:road-sports/association-football] In the Middle Ages, one notable game with similarities to modern football was *calcio storico fiorentino*, which originated in Florence, Italy.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Another medieval sport that can be considered a form of early football is *la soule* (or *choule*), played in France from the 12th century, in which the ball was propelled by hands, feet, and sticks.
[src:road-sports/association-football] As with pre-codified mob football, the antecedent of all modern football codes, these medieval games involved more handling of the ball than kicking it.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The Cambridge rules, first drawn up at the University of Cambridge in 1848, were particularly influential in the development of subsequent codes, including association football.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The Cambridge rules were written at Trinity College, Cambridge, at a meeting attended by representatives from Eton, Harrow, Rugby, Winchester, and Shrewsbury schools.
[src:road-sports/association-football] During the 1850s, many clubs unconnected to schools or universities were formed throughout the English-speaking world to play various forms of football.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Some came up with their own distinct codes of rules, most notably the Sheffield Football Club, formed by former public school pupils in 1857, which led to the formation of a Sheffield FA in 1867.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In 1862, John Charles Thring of Uppingham School also devised an influential set of rules.
[src:road-sports/association-football] These ongoing efforts contributed to the formation of the Football Association (the FA) in 1863, which first met on the morning of 26 October 1863 at the Freemasons' Tavern in Great Queen Street, London.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The only school to be represented on this occasion was Charterhouse.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The Freemasons' Tavern was the setting for five more meetings of the FA between October and December 1863; the English FA eventually issued the first comprehensive set of rules named Laws of the Game, forming modern football.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The laws included bans on running with the ball in hand and hacking (kicking an opponent in the shins), tripping and holding.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Eleven clubs, under the charge of FA secretary Ebenezer Cobb Morley, ratified the original thirteen laws of the game.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The sticking point was hacking, which a twelfth club at the meeting, Blackheath FC, had wanted to keep, resulting in their withdrawal from the FA.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Other English rugby clubs followed this lead and did not join the FA, and instead in 1871, along with Blackheath, formed the Rugby Football Union.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The 1863 FA rules included handling of the ball by "marks" and the lack of a crossbar, making the game remarkably similar to Victorian rules football, which was being developed around the same time in Australia.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The Sheffield FA played by its own rules until the 1870s, with the FA absorbing some of its rules until there was little difference between the games.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The world's oldest football competition is the FA Cup, which was founded by the footballer and cricketer Charles W.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Alcock, and has been contested by English teams since 1872.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The first official international football match also took place in 1872, between Scotland and England in Glasgow, again at the instigation of Alcock.
[src:road-sports/association-football] England is also home to the world's first football league, which was founded in Birmingham in 1888 by Aston Villa director William McGregor.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The original format contained 12 clubs from the Midlands and Northern England.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The Laws of the Game are determined by the International Football Association Board (IFAB).
[src:road-sports/association-football] The board was formed in 1886 after a meeting in Manchester of the Football Association, the Scottish Football Association, the Football Association of Wales, and the Irish Football Association.
[src:road-sports/association-football] FIFA, the international football body, was formed in Paris in 1904 and declared that they would adhere to the Laws of the Game of the Football Association.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The growing popularity of the international game led to the admittance of FIFA representatives to the IFAB in 1913.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The board consists of four representatives from FIFA and one representative from each of the four British associations.
[src:road-sports/association-football] For most of the 20th century, Europe and South America were the dominant regions in association football.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The FIFA World Cup, inaugurated in 1930, became the main stage for players of both continents to show their worth and the strength of their national teams.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In the second half of the century, the European Cup and the Copa Libertadores were created, and the champions of these two club competitions would contest the Intercontinental Cup to prove which team was the best in the world.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In the 21st century, South America has continued to produce some of the best footballers in the world, but its clubs have fallen behind the still dominant European clubs, which often sign the best players from Latin America and elsewhere.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Meanwhile, football has improved in Africa, Asia, and North America, and nowadays, these regions are at least on equal grounds with South America in club football.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Football is played at a professional level all over the world.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Millions of people regularly go to football stadiums to follow their favourite teams, whilst billions more watch the game on television or on the internet.
[src:road-sports/association-football] A very large number of people also play football at an amateur level.
[src:road-sports/association-football] According to a survey conducted by FIFA published in 2001, over 240 million people from more than 200 countries regularly play football.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Football has the highest global television audience in sport.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In many parts of the world, football evokes great passions and plays an important role in the life of individual fans, local communities, and even nations.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Ryszard Kapuściński says that Europeans who are polite, modest, or humble fall easily into rage when playing or watching football games.
[src:road-sports/association-football] By contrast, football is widely considered to have been the final proximate cause for the Football War in June 1969 between El Salvador and Honduras.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The sport also exacerbated tensions at the beginning of the Croatian War of Independence of the 1990s, when a match between Dinamo Zagreb and Red Star Belgrade degenerated into rioting in May 1990.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The popularity of association football has been connected to identity fusion with replacement fandom collective identities.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Women's association football has historically seen opposition, with national associations severely curbing its development and several outlawing it completely.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Nevertheless, women have been playing football and similar games for as long as such games have existed.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Frescoes from the Han dynasty (25–220 CE) depict female figures playing the ancient Chinese game *cuju*.
[src:road-sports/association-football] There are also reports of annual football matches played by women in Midlothian, Scotland, during the 1790s.
[src:road-sports/association-football] There is documented evidence of women's early involvement in association football.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Informal matches between Scotland and England are reported to have taken place in 1881, but are not officially recognised by the respective football associations.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The first women's match recorded by the Scottish Football Association took place in 1892 in Glasgow.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In England, the first recorded game of football between women took place in 1895.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The best-documented early European team was founded by activist Nettie Honeyball in England in 1894: the British Ladies' Football Club.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Honeyball considered women's involvement in football as part of the emancipation movement.
[src:road-sports/association-football] She and others like her paved the way for women's football.
[src:road-sports/association-football] However, the women's game was frowned upon by the British football associations and continued without their support.
[src:road-sports/association-football] It has been suggested that this was motivated by a perceived threat to the "masculinity" of the game.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Women's football became popular on a large scale at the time of the First World War, when female employment in heavy industry spurred the growth of the game, much as it had done for men decades earlier.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The most successful team of the era was Dick, Kerr Ladies F.C. of Preston, England.
[src:road-sports/association-football] They played in one of the first women's international matches against a French XI team in 1920, and also made up most of the England team against a Scottish Ladies XI in the same year, winning 22–0.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In the early 20th century, women's football in the United Kingdom was mostly associated with charity matches.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Players and football writers have argued that this ban was, in fact, due to envy of the large crowds that women's matches attracted, and because the FA had no control over the money made from the women's game.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The FA ban led to the formation of the short-lived English Ladies Football Association and play moved to rugby grounds.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Women's football also faced bans in several other countries, notably in Brazil from 1941 to 1979, in France from 1941 to 1970, and in West Germany from 1955 to 1970.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In spite of the resistance from governing bodies, British women continued to play football.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Restrictions against female participation in the sport began to be reduced in the late 1960s and the 1970s.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The Italian women's football league was established in 1968.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In December 1969, the Women's Football Association was formed in England, with the sport eventually becoming the most prominent team sport for women in the United Kingdom.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Two unofficial women's World Cups were organised by the FIEFF in 1970 and in 1971.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Also in 1971, UEFA members voted to officially recognise women's football, while the Football Association rescinded the ban that prohibited women from playing on association members' pitches in England.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The first Asian Women's Championship happened in 1975, initially without the approval of the AFC, but later recognised by them.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Women's football still faces many struggles, but its worldwide growth has seen major competitions being launched at both the national and international levels, mirroring the men's competitions.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The FIFA Women's World Cup was inaugurated in 1991: the first tournament was held in China, featuring 12 teams from the six confederations.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The World Cup has been held every four years since; by 2019, it had expanded to 24 national teams, and 1.12 billion viewers watched the competition.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Four years later, FIFA targeted the 32-team 2023 Women's World Cup at an audience of 2 billion, while more than 1.5 million tickets were sold, setting a Women's World Cup record.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Women's football has been an Olympic event since 1996.
[src:road-sports/association-football] North America is the dominant region in women's football, with the United States winning the most FIFA Women's World Cups and Olympic tournaments.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Europe and Asia come second and third in terms of international success, and the women's game has been improving in South America.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Association football is played in accordance with a set of rules known as the Laws of the Game.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The game is played using a spherical ball of 68–70 cm (27–28 in) circumference, known as the *football* (or *soccer ball*).
[src:road-sports/association-football] Two teams of eleven players each compete to get the ball into the other team's goal (between the posts and under the bar), thereby scoring a goal.
[src:road-sports/association-football] There are situations where a goal can be disallowed, such as an offside call or a foul in the build-up to the goal.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The team that has scored more goals at the end of the game is the winner; if both teams have scored an equal number of goals then the game is a draw.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Each team is led by a captain who has only one official responsibility as mandated by the Laws of the Game: to represent their team in the coin toss before kick-off or penalty kicks.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The primary law is that players other than goalkeepers may not deliberately handle the ball with their hands or arms during play, though they must use both their hands during a throw-in restart.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Although players usually use their feet to move the ball around, they may use any part of their body (notably, "heading" with the forehead) other than their hands or arms.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Within normal play, all players are free to play the ball in any direction and move throughout the pitch, though players may not pass to teammates who are in an offside position.
[src:road-sports/association-football] During gameplay, players attempt to create goal-scoring opportunities through individual control of the ball, such as by dribbling, passing the ball to a teammate, and by taking shots at the goal, which is guarded by the opposing goalkeeper.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Opposing players may try to regain control of the ball by intercepting a pass or through tackling the opponent in possession of the ball; however, physical contact between opponents is restricted.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Football is generally a free-flowing game, with play stopping only when the ball has left the field of play or when play is stopped by the referee for an infringement of the rules.
[src:road-sports/association-football] After a stoppage, play recommences with a specified restart.
[src:road-sports/association-football] At a professional level, most matches produce only a few goals.
[src:road-sports/association-football] For example, the 2022–23 season of the English Premier League produced an average of 2.85 goals per match.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The Laws of the Game do not specify any player positions other than goalkeeper, but a number of specialised roles have evolved.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Broadly, these include three main categories: strikers, or forwards, whose main task is to score goals; defenders, who specialise in preventing their opponents from scoring; and midfielders, who dispossess the opposition and keep possession of the ball to pass it to the forwards on their team.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Players in these positions are referred to as outfield players, to distinguish them from the goalkeeper.
[src:road-sports/association-football] These positions are further subdivided according to the area of the field in which the player spends the most time.
[src:road-sports/association-football] For example, there are central defenders and left and right midfielders.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The ten outfield players may be arranged in any combination.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The number of players in each position determines the style of the team's play; more forwards and fewer defenders creates a more aggressive and offensive-minded game, while the reverse creates a slower, more defensive style of play.
[src:road-sports/association-football] While players typically spend most of the game in a specific position, there are few restrictions on player movement, and players can switch positions at any time.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The layout of a team's players is known as a *formation*.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Defining the team's formation and tactics is usually the prerogative of the team's manager.
[src:road-sports/association-football] There are seventeen laws in the official Laws of the Game, each containing a collection of stipulations and guidelines.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The same laws are designed to apply to all levels of football for both sexes, although certain modifications for groups such as juniors, seniors and people with physical disabilities are permitted.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The laws are often framed in broad terms, which allow flexibility in their application depending on the nature of the game.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The Laws of the Game are published by FIFA, but are maintained by the IFAB.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In addition to the seventeen laws, numerous IFAB decisions and other directives contribute to the regulation of association football.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Within the United States, Major League Soccer used a distinct ruleset during the 1990s, and the NFHS and NCAA still use rulesets that are comparable to, but different from, the IFAB Laws.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Each team consists of a maximum of eleven players (excluding substitutes), one of whom must be the goalkeeper.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Competition rules may state a minimum number of players required to constitute a team, which is usually seven.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Goalkeepers are the only players allowed to play the ball with their hands or arms, provided they do so within the penalty area in front of their own goal.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Though there are a variety of positions in which the outfield (non-goalkeeper) players are strategically placed by a coach, these positions are not defined or required by the Laws.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The basic equipment or *kit* players are required to wear includes a shirt, shorts, socks, footwear and adequate shin guards.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Wearing an athletic supporter with protective cup is recommended for male players by medical experts and professionals.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Headgear is not a required piece of equipment, but players may choose to wear it to protect themselves from head injury.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Players are forbidden to wear or use anything that is dangerous to themselves or another player, such as jewellery or watches.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The goalkeeper must wear clothing that is easily distinguishable from that worn by the other players and the match officials.
[src:road-sports/association-football] A number of players may be replaced by substitutes during the course of the game.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The maximum number of substitutions permitted in most competitive international and domestic league games is five in 90 minutes, with each team being allowed one more if the game should go into extra-time; the permitted number may vary in other competitions or in friendly matches.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Common reasons for a substitution include injury, tiredness, ineffectiveness, a tactical switch, or timewasting at the end of a finely poised game.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In standard adult matches, a player who has been substituted may not take further part in a match.
[src:road-sports/association-football] IFAB recommends "that a match should not continue if there are fewer than seven players in either team".
[src:road-sports/association-football] Any decision regarding points awarded for abandoned games is left to the individual football associations.
[src:road-sports/association-football] A game is officiated by a referee, who has "full authority to enforce the Laws of the Game in connection with the match to which he has been appointed" (Law 5), and whose decisions are final.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The referee is assisted by two assistant referees.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In many high-level games there is also a fourth official who assists the referee and may replace another official should the need arise.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Goal line technology is used to measure if the whole ball has crossed the goal-line thereby determining whether a goal has been scored or not; this was brought in to prevent controversy.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Video assistant referees (VAR) have also been increasingly introduced in high-level matches to assist officials through video replays to correct clear and obvious mistakes.
[src:road-sports/association-football] There are four types of calls that can be reviewed: mistaken identity in awarding a red or yellow card, goals and whether there was a violation during the build-up, direct red card decisions, and penalty decisions.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The ball is spherical with a circumference of between 68 and 70 cm (27 and 28 in), a weight in the range of 410 to 450 g (14 to 16 oz), and a pressure between 0.6 and 1.1 standard atmospheres (8.5 and 15.6 pounds per square inch) at sea level.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In the past the ball was made up of leather panels sewn together, with a latex bladder for pressurisation, but modern balls at all levels of the game are now synthetic.
[src:road-sports/association-football] As the Laws were formulated in England, and were initially administered solely by the four British football associations within IFAB, the standard dimensions of a football pitch were originally expressed in imperial units.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The Laws now express dimensions with approximate metric equivalents (followed by traditional units in brackets), though use of imperial units remains popular in English-speaking countries with a relatively recent history of metrication (or only partial metrication), such as Britain.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The length of the pitch, or field, for international adult matches is in the range of 100–110 m (110–120 yd) and the width is in the range of 64–75 m (70–80 yd).
[src:road-sports/association-football] Fields for non-international matches may be 90–120 m (100–130 yd) in length and 45–90 m (50–100 yd) in width, provided the pitch does not become square.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In 2008, the IFAB initially approved a fixed size of 105 m (115 yd) long and 68 m (74 yd) wide as a standard pitch dimension for international matches; however, this decision was later put on hold and was never actually implemented.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The longer boundary lines are *touchlines*, while the shorter boundaries (on which the goals are placed) are *goal lines*.
[src:road-sports/association-football] A rectangular goal is positioned on each goal line, midway between the two touchlines.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The inner edges of the vertical goal posts must be 7.32 m (24 ft) apart, and the lower edge of the horizontal crossbar supported by the goal posts must be 2.44 m (8 ft) above the ground.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Nets are usually placed behind the goal, but are not required by the Laws.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In front of the goal is the penalty area.
[src:road-sports/association-football] This area is marked by the goal line, two lines starting on the goal line 16.5 m (18 yd) from the goalposts and extending 16.5 m (18 yd) into the pitch perpendicular to the goal line, and a line joining them.
[src:road-sports/association-football] This area has a number of functions, the most prominent being to mark where the goalkeeper may handle the ball and where a penalty foul by a member of the defending team becomes punishable by a penalty kick.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Other markings define the position of the ball or players at kick-offs, goal kicks, penalty kicks and corner kicks.
[src:road-sports/association-football] A standard adult football match consists of two halves of 45 minutes each.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Each half runs continuously, meaning that the clock is not stopped when the ball is out of play.
[src:road-sports/association-football] There is usually a 15-minute half-time break between halves.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The end of the match is known as full-time.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The referee is the official timekeeper for the match, and may make an allowance for time lost through substitutions, injured players requiring attention, or other stoppages.
[src:road-sports/association-football] This added time is called "additional time" in FIFA documents, but is most commonly referred to as *stoppage time* or *injury time*, while *lost time* can also be used as a synonym.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The duration of stoppage time is at the sole discretion of the referee.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Stoppage time does not fully compensate for the time in which the ball is out of play, and a 90-minute game typically involves about an hour of "effective playing time".
[src:road-sports/association-football] The referee alone signals the end of the match.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In matches where a fourth official is appointed, towards the end of the half, the referee signals how many minutes of stoppage time they intend to add.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The fourth official then informs the players and spectators by holding up a board showing this number.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The signalled stoppage time may be further extended by the referee.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Added time was introduced because of an incident in 1891 during a match between Stoke and Aston Villa.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Trailing 1–0 with two minutes remaining, Stoke were awarded a penalty kick.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Villa's goalkeeper deliberately kicked the ball far out of play; by the time it was recovered, the clock had run out and the game was over, leaving Stoke unable to attempt the penalty.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The same rule also states that the duration of either half is extended until a penalty kick to be taken or retaken is completed; thus, no game can end with an uncompleted penalty.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Due to the relatively high ambient temperatures in some regions, cooling breaks for the players were introduced.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Breaks could take place at the referee's discretion after the 30th minute of each half if the wet-bulb globe temperature exceeded 32 °C (90 °F); the breaks would last 3 minutes, with this time made up by an extended period of stoppage time at the end of the half.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In league competitions, games may end in a draw.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In knockout competitions where a winner is required, various methods may be employed to break such a deadlock; some competitions may invoke replays.
[src:road-sports/association-football] A game tied at the end of regulation time may go into extra time, which consists of two further 15-minute periods.
[src:road-sports/association-football] If the score is still tied after extra time, some competitions allow the use of penalty shoot-outs (previously known in the Laws of the Game as "kicks from the penalty mark") to determine which team will progress to the next stage of the tournament or be the champion.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Goals scored during extra time periods count towards the final score of the game, but kicks from the penalty mark are only used to decide the team that progresses to the next part of the tournament, with goals scored in a penalty shoot-out not making up part of the final score.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In competitions using two-legged matches, each team competes at home once, with an aggregate score from the two matches deciding which team progresses.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Where aggregates are equal, the away goals rule may be used to determine the winners, in which case the winner is the team that scored the most goals in the leg they played away from home.
[src:road-sports/association-football] If the result is still equal, extra time and potentially a penalty shoot-out are required.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Under the Laws, the two basic states of play during a game are *ball in play* and *ball out of play*.
[src:road-sports/association-football] From the beginning of each playing period with a kick-off until the end of the playing period, the ball is in play at all times, except when either the ball leaves the field of play, or play is stopped by the referee.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Players are cautioned with a yellow card, and dismissed from the game with a red card.
[src:road-sports/association-football] A foul occurs when a player commits an offence listed in the Laws of the Game while the ball is in play.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The offences that constitute a foul are listed in Law 12.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Handling the ball deliberately, tripping an opponent, or pushing an opponent, are examples of "penal fouls", punishable by a direct free kick or penalty kick depending on where the offence occurred.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Other fouls are punishable by an indirect free kick.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The referee may punish a player's or substitute's misconduct by a caution (yellow card) or dismissal (red card).
[src:road-sports/association-football] A second yellow card in the same game leads to a red card, which results in a dismissal.
[src:road-sports/association-football] A player given a yellow card is said to have been "booked", the referee writing the player's name in their official notebook.
[src:road-sports/association-football] If a player has been dismissed, no substitute can be brought on in their place and the player may not participate in further play.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Misconduct may occur at any time, and while the offences that constitute misconduct are listed, the definitions are broad.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In particular, the offence of "unsporting behaviour" may be used to deal with most events that violate the spirit of the game, even if they are not listed as specific offences.
[src:road-sports/association-football] A referee can show a yellow or red card to a player, substitute, substituted player, and to non-players such as managers and support staff.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Rather than stopping play, the referee may allow play to continue if doing so will benefit the team against which an offence has been committed.
[src:road-sports/association-football] This is known as "playing an advantage".
[src:road-sports/association-football] The referee may "call back" play and penalise the original offence if the anticipated advantage does not ensue within "a few seconds".
[src:road-sports/association-football] Even if an offence is not penalised due to advantage being played, the offender may still be sanctioned for misconduct at the next stoppage of play.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The referee's decision in all on-pitch matters is considered final.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The score of a match cannot be altered after the game, even if later evidence shows that decisions (including whether a goal was awarded or not) were incorrect.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Along with the general administration of the sport, football associations and competition organisers also enforce good conduct in wider aspects of the game, dealing with issues such as comments to the press, clubs' financial management, doping, age fraud and match fixing.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Most competitions enforce mandatory suspensions for players who are sent off in a game.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Some on-field incidents, if considered very serious (such as allegations of racial abuse), may result in competitions deciding to impose heavier sanctions than those normally associated with a red card.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Some associations allow for appeals against player suspensions incurred on-field if clubs feel a referee was incorrect or unduly harsh.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Sanctions for such infractions may be levied on individuals or on clubs as a whole.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Penalties may include fines, point deductions (in league competitions) or even expulsion from competitions.
[src:road-sports/association-football] For example, the English Football League deduct 12 points from any team that enters financial administration.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Among other administrative sanctions are penalties against game forfeiture.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Teams that forfeit a game or are forfeited against are awarded a technical loss or win.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The recognised international governing body of football (and associated games, such as futsal and beach soccer) is FIFA.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The FIFA headquarters are located in Zürich, Switzerland.
[src:road-sports/association-football] National associations (or national federations) oversee football within individual countries.
[src:road-sports/association-football] 211 national associations are affiliated both with FIFA and with their respective continental confederations.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Other national associations may be members of continental confederations but otherwise not participate in FIFA competitions.
[src:road-sports/association-football] While FIFA is responsible for organising international competitions and enforcing most international regulations, the Laws of the Game are set by the IFAB, where each of the four UK associations holds one vote and FIFA collectively holds four votes.
[src:road-sports/association-football] International competitions in association football principally consist of two varieties: competitions involving representative national teams or those involving clubs based in multiple nations and national leagues.
[src:road-sports/association-football] *International football*, without qualification, most often refers to the former.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In the case of international club competition, it is the country of origin of the clubs involved, not the nationalities of their players, that renders the competition international in nature.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The major international competition in football and the most prestigious is the World Cup, organised by FIFA.
[src:road-sports/association-football] This competition has taken place every four years since 1930, with the exception of the 1942 and 1946 tournaments, which were cancelled because of World War II.
[src:road-sports/association-football] As of 2022, over 200 national teams compete in qualifying tournaments within the scope of continental confederations for a place in the finals.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The finals tournament involved 32 national teams (expanding to 48 teams for the 2026 tournament) competing over a four-week period.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The World Cup is the world's most widely viewed and most followed sporting event, with the 2022 tournament estimated to be watched by 5 billion people, more than 60% of the global population.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The 1958 World Cup saw the emergence of Pelé as a global sporting star, a period that coincided with "the explosive spread of television, which massively amplified his presence everywhere".
[src:road-sports/association-football] The current champions are Argentina, who won their third title at the 2022 tournament in Qatar.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The FIFA Women's World Cup has been held every four years since 1991.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Under the tournament's current format that was expanded in 2023, national teams vie for 31 slots in a three-year qualification phase, while the host nation's team enters automatically as the 32nd slot.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The current champions are Spain, after winning their first title in the 2023 tournament.
[src:road-sports/association-football] There has been a football tournament at every Summer Olympic Games since 1900, except at the 1932 games in Los Angeles when FIFA and the International Olympic Committee (IOC) had disagreed over the status of amateur players.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Before the inception of the World Cup, the Olympics (especially during the 1920s) were the most prestigious international event.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Originally, the tournament was for amateurs only.
[src:road-sports/association-football] As professionalism spread around the world, the gap in quality between the World Cup and the Olympics widened.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The countries that benefited most were the Soviet Bloc countries of Eastern Europe, where top athletes were state-sponsored while retaining their status as amateurs.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Between 1948 and 1980, 23 out of 27 Olympic medals were won by Eastern Europe, with only Sweden (gold in 1948 and bronze in 1952), Denmark (bronze in 1948 and silver in 1960) and Japan (bronze in 1968) breaking their dominance.
[src:road-sports/association-football] For the 1984 Los Angeles Games, the IOC allowed professional players to compete.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Since 1992, male competitors must be under 23 years old, although since 1996, three players over the age of 23 have been allowed per squad.
[src:road-sports/association-football] A women's tournament was added in 1996; in contrast to the men's event, full international sides without age restrictions play the women's Olympic tournament.
[src:road-sports/association-football] After the World Cup, the most important international football competitions are the continental championships, which are organised by each continental confederation and contested between national teams.
[src:road-sports/association-football] These are the European Championship (UEFA), the Copa América (CONMEBOL), the Africa Cup of Nations (CAF), the Asian Cup (AFC), the Gold Cup (CONCACAF) and the Nations Cup (OFC).
[src:road-sports/association-football] These competitions are not strictly limited to members of the continental confederations, with guest teams from other continents sometimes invited to compete.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The FIFA Confederations Cup was contested by the winners of all six continental championships, the current FIFA World Cup champions, and the country which was hosting the next World Cup.
[src:road-sports/association-football] This was generally regarded as a warm-up tournament for the upcoming FIFA World Cup and did not carry the same prestige as the World Cup itself.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The tournament was discontinued following the 2017 edition, with its calendar slot replaced by an expanded FIFA Club World Cup.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The Finalissima was revived in 2022, and is contested between the Copa América and European Championship winners.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The UEFA Nations League and the CONCACAF Nations League were introduced in the late 2010s to replace international friendlies during the two-year cycle between major tournaments.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The most prestigious competitions in club football are the respective continental championships, which are generally contested between national champions, for example, the UEFA Champions League in Europe and the Copa Libertadores in South America.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The winners of each continental competition contest the FIFA Intercontinental Cup, held annually, and the FIFA Club World Cup, held once every four years.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In each country, football clubs are usually federated in associations or leagues that organise official tournaments among themselves, from which the champion of each country and the teams that will participate in international club tournaments emerge.
[src:road-sports/association-football] There is no single system of competitions, and each national league organises them according to its own traditions.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The governing bodies in each country operate league systems in a domestic season, normally comprising several divisions, in which the teams gain points throughout the season depending on results, usually three points for a win, one for a draw and zero for a defeat.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Teams are put into tables, placed in order according to points accrued.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In the Old World (Africa, Asia and Europe), it is common for each team to play every other team in its league at home and away in each season, in a round-robin tournament.
[src:road-sports/association-football] At the end of a season, which typically runs from August to May, the top team is declared the champion.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The top few teams may be promoted to a higher division, and one or more of the teams finishing at the bottom are relegated to a lower division.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The teams finishing at the top of a country's league may also be eligible to play in international club competitions in the following season.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Most countries supplement the league system with one or more "cup" competitions organised on a knock-out basis.
[src:road-sports/association-football] These include the domestic cup, which may be open to all eligible teams in a country's league system—both professional and amateur—and is organised by the national federation.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Some countries' top divisions feature highly-paid star players; in smaller countries, lower divisions, and many women's clubs, players may be part-timers with a second job, or amateurs.
[src:road-sports/association-football] The top five European leagues – Premier League (England), Bundesliga (Germany), La Liga (Spain), Serie A (Italy), and Ligue 1 (France) – attract most of the world's best players and, during the 2006–07 season, each of these leagues had a total wage cost in excess of €600 million.
[src:road-sports/association-football] These leagues also generated a combined €17.2 billion in revenue in the 2021–22 season from television contracts, matchday tickets, sponsorships, and other sources.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In the 2022–23 season, clubs in Europe's "big five" leagues had an aggregate wage cost of €13 billion, with each league spending more than €1.8 billion in wages.
[src:road-sports/association-football] In contrast, the combined revenue of these leagues was €19.6 billion.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Variants of association football have been codified for teams of reduced size, such as five-a-side football; for non-traditional playing environments, including beach soccer, futsal and indoor soccer; and for athletes with disabilities (Paralympic football).
[src:road-sports/association-football] Street football can be played with only minimal equipment – a basic game can be played on almost any open area of reasonable size with just a ball made from almost any material and items to mark the positions of the goalposts.
[src:road-sports/association-football] Such informal games can have team sizes that vary from eleven-a-side, can use a limited or modified subset of the official rules, and can be self-officiated by the players.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In many sports leagues and competitions, a team wears its away kit only when its primary kit would clash with the colours of the home team, while other sports leagues and competitions may mandate that away teams must always wear an alternative kit regardless of a potential colour clash.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The latter is common in North American sports, where "colour vs. colour" games (e.g., blue uniforms vs. red uniforms) are a rarity, having been discouraged in the era of black-and-white television.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Almost all road uniforms are white in gridiron football (including in the Canadian Football League, the National Football League and NCAA football) and the National Hockey League, while in baseball, visitors typically wear grey.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In the National Basketball Association and NCAA basketball, home uniforms are white or yellow, and visiting teams wear the darker colour.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Home teams in some leagues and competitions may also have the option to wear away colours at certain home games, and the away team then has to wear the opposite (if applicable).
[src:road-sports/away-colours] At some clubs, the away kit has become more popular than the home version.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Replica home and away kits are usually available for fans to buy.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Some teams also have produced third-choice kits, or even old-fashioned throwback uniforms.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In many sports, the colour contrast is only required for the upper body garment, and thus a team's home and away kit may both have the same coloured pants or shorts.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] It has traditionally been the opposite in Australian rules football where the home team wears dark shorts and the away team wears white shorts.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] ' red (left) and white (right) jersey in 2021.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In American football, the home team has the choice to wear white or its official team colour and the visiting team must wear the opposite.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In the National Football League (NFL), most teams often wear their "official team colour" at home, with the road team being assigned to wear white in most cases.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] White road uniforms gained prominence with the rise of television in the 1950s.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] A "white vs. colour" game was easier to follow in the black-and-white television era.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] According to Phil Hecken of uni-watch.com, "colour vs. colour" games were actually the norm until the mid-1950s.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Even long after the advent of colour television, the use of white jerseys has remained in almost every game.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The NFL's current rules require that a team's home uniforms must be "either white or official team colour" throughout the season, "and visiting clubs must wear the opposite".
[src:road-sports/away-colours] If a team insists on wearing its home uniforms on the road, the NFL Commissioner must judge on whether their uniforms are "of sufficient contrast" with those of their opponents.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The road team may instead wear a third jersey, such as the Seattle Seahawks' "Wolf Grey" alternate.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Cleveland Browns wore white for every home game of the 1955 season.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The only times they wore brown were for games at Philadelphia and New York, when the Eagles and Giants chose to wear white.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In 1964, the Baltimore Colts, Cleveland Browns, Minnesota Vikings and Los Angeles Rams wore white regularly for their home games.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Louis Cardinals also wore white for several of their home games.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] While most teams switched back to their coloured uniforms the next year, the Rams and Browns still regularly wore white until the 1970s, with the Browns even continung it until their temporary deactivation in 1996.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Since returning in 1999, the Browns have on occasion worn white at home during the regular season, but for the most part have relegated it to the preseason while wearing brown jerseys for the regular season.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Until 1964, the Dallas Cowboys had worn blue at home, but it was not an official rule that teams should wear their official colours at home.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The use of white jerseys was introduced by general manager (GM) Tex Schramm, who wanted fans to see a variety of opponents' jersey colours at home games and continues to do so today.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] White has also been worn regularly at home by the Miami Dolphins, Washington Commanders, and several other NFL teams.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Teams in cities with hot climates often choose white jerseys at home during the first half of the season in late-summer and autumn, because light colours absorb and retain less heat in sunlight.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] These hot climate teams include several clubs in the Southern United States such as the Carolina Panthers, Houston Texans, Jacksonville Jaguars, New Orleans Saints,Tampa Bay Buccaneers, and Tennessee Titans.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Dolphins in particular will generally stay in white most of the season due to Miami's winter climate, typically only wearing their coloured jerseys for home night games, and 1 PM games very late in the season.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Seattle Seahawks had never worn white jerseys at home until their September 24 home game against the Carolina Panthers in 2023.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] During the successful Joe Gibbs era, Washington chose to wear white exclusively at home in the 1980s and 1990s, including the 1982 NFC Championship Game against Dallas.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Since 2001, they have chosen to wear white jerseys and burgundy jerseys roughly equally in their home games, but they still wear white against the Cowboys.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] When Gibbs returned from 2004 to 2007, they wore white at home exclusively.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In 2007, they wore a white throwback jersey.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Dallas Cowboys' blue jersey has been popularly viewed to be "jinxed" because of defeats at Super Bowl V in 1971 (when they were assigned to wear their blue jerseys as the designated 'home' team), and in the 1968 divisional playoffs at Cleveland, Don Meredith's final game as a Cowboys player.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Dallas's only victory in a conference championship or Super Bowl wearing the blue jerseys was in the 1978 NFC Championship game at the Los Angeles Rams.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Super Bowl rules later changed to allow the designated home team to pick their choice of jersey.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] White was chosen by the Cowboys (XIII, XXVII), the Redskins (XVII), the Pittsburgh Steelers (XL), the Denver Broncos (50), the New England Patriots (LII), and the Buccaneers (LV).
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Broncos and Steelers normally wear colours at home, but Pittsburgh had worn white in three road playoff wins, while Denver cited its previous Super Bowl success in white jerseys (XXXIII), while being 0–4 when wearing orange in Super Bowls.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Occasionally, teams playing against Dallas at home wear their white jerseys to attempt to invoke the "curse", as when the Philadelphia Eagles hosted the Cowboys in the 1980 NFC Championship Game.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Louis Cardinals and New York Giants followed suit in the 1980s, and the Carolina Panthers did so from 1995 until 2006, including two playoff games.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Houston Texans did so in 2002, beating Dallas in their inaugural regular season game.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] More recently, the Patriots and then-St.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The originator of white home jerseys in the NFL at Dallas, Tex Schramm, said he did not believe in the curse.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] While they had only done so twice, both to "jinx" Dallas, during the 21 years they played in St.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Louis, since returning to Los Angeles in 2016, the Rams, temporarily playing in the same stadium as they had in the 1960s, have worn white at home as a conscious tribute to the teams of that era.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Coloured road uniforms were used in the World Football League (WFL) during its short period of existence in 1974–75, with the home team wearing white, and college football teams must base their road uniform around a white jersey.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] National Federation of State High School Associations rules, which are used by every state for high school football except Texas, require the visiting team to wear a white jersey and the home team to wear a dark jersey.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The University Interscholastic League, which governs Texas public high schools, plays by NCAA football rules, which allow for white jerseys to be worn by the home team with prior notification to the visiting team.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] While a team's primary kit rarely undergoes major changes, the second colours tend to vary over time and sometimes by tournament.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Some away kits are a modification of the home colours (for example a reversal of primary and secondary colours), other away kits are considerably different from home kits.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Several club and national sides have favourite away colours which might remain the same more or less continuously.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Often these are colours that were used in famous victories; for instance Brazil (blue) and A.C.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Many professional clubs also have an official third kit.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Some teams opt to wear their away colours even when not required to by a clash of colours, or when they are the home team and therefore get first dibs on their colour.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] England sometimes play in red away shirts, as the team wore red when it won the 1966 World Cup.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Milan chose to wear all-white in the 2007 UEFA Champions League final as they considered it their "lucky shirt" (Italian: *maglia fortunata*).
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In some title-deciding matches, a team has won the game wearing its away kit, but changed to home shirts for the trophy presentation – most notably when Spain won the 2010 World Cup final, changing from dark-blue away to red home shirts to lift the trophy.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In some cases both teams have been forced to wear their second choice away kits; such as in some World Cup matches *(see section below)*.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] During the 1998-99 UEFA Champions League, Manchester United had to wear their away colours in both of their group stage matches against F.C.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Barcelona, not just away at Camp Nou but also home at Old Trafford too due to a ruling by UEFA that in the event of a clash, the home team had to change their colours.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In England in 1890, the Football League, which had been formed two years earlier, ruled that no two member teams could register similar colours, so as to avoid clashes.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] This rule was later abandoned in favour of one stipulating that all teams must have a second set of shirts in a different colour available.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Initially the home team was required to change colours in the event of a clash, but in 1921 the rule was amended to require the away team to change.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In 1927 the Scottish Football Association decreed a different solution, whereby home teams wore white shorts and away teams black shorts, but this rule was rescinded in 1929.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] It is normal for individual competitions to specify that all outfield players on a team must wear the same colours, though the Law states only "The two teams must wear colours that distinguish them from each other and the match officials".
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In the event of a colour clash, the away team must change to a different colour.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Away kits were often worn by both teams in English FA Cup matches.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Until 1989–90, its competition rules stated: "Where the colours of the two competing clubs are similar, both clubs must change unless alternative arrangements are mutually agreed by the competing clubs".
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Clubs sometimes needed to find makeshift third kits for their players.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Many FA Cup finals were played under these rules, the last being the 1982 final and its replay.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In European competition, the 1968 European Cup final was played under similar rules.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The old FA Cup rules, with almost identical wording, are still used in semis and finals by many county and district football associations in England.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Three teams have won the FIFA World Cup final in their away colours – in 1958 (Brazil), 1966 (England), and 2010 (Spain); though England was the home team for the 1966 tournament and Brazil was the home team for the 1958 final.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] At international level, away kits are sometimes worn by both teams in a match.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] FIFA rules state that in exceptional cases, both teams may be asked by the referee or match commissioner to wear different colours.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] This is most likely to happen in World Cup matches with large numbers of black-and-white television viewers, so that the teams' kits also differ in tone (light and dark).
[src:road-sports/away-colours] World Cup teams often have to make changes that would be unlikely in domestic or untelevised games.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In 1957 Scotland borrowed home team Switzerland's white away shirts to avoid clashing on black-and-white television.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In 1970 England and Czechoslovakia were allowed to play in sky blue and white, respectively, which caused confusion for black-and-white viewers and England manager Alf Ramsey.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] England reverted to red away shirts against West Germany.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Netherlands and Brazil played their 1974 World Cup game in white and dark blue respectively, rather than their first choices of orange and yellow.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] FIFA's regulations for the 2014 World Cup mandate that "teams need to have two very distinguishable shirts – where one is a lighter colour and the other is a darker one".
[src:road-sports/away-colours] At the 2014 World Cup, Croatia were allowed to wear red-and-white checked shirts, instead of blue, against Brazil, only after Croatia appealed FIFA's original decision.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] England were not allowed to wear red away shirts, and instead were made to wear white against Uruguay, due to an apparent clash with officials' uniforms.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Before the 2014 tournament, FIFA decreed that Spain's all-red home kit and all-black away kit were not sufficient as they were both considered dark tones.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] FIFA forced Spain to produce an all-white third kit.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The match between the Netherlands and Spain was played in the Netherlands' dark blue away kits and Spain's white third-choice kits.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In the 2018 FIFA World Cup third place match, both Belgium and England wore their away colours of yellow and red by choice, respectively, despite their home colours of red vs white not clashing.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Denmark and Australia also wore their away kits in a group stage match, after Danish player Thomas Delaney revealed in a phone call to a radio station that he is colourblind.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Australian Football League legislates that the home team has the right to choose what home colours they play in for home games during the home and away season.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Traditionally in Australian football and first introduced into VFL in 1924 the home team wears dark shorts while the away team wears white shorts.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In contrast to other sports, the concept of away colours is not prominent, with clubs traditionally wearing their home guernseys week in week out, with the colour of a team's shorts distinguishing between home teams and away teams.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The concept of home and away colours first became prominent during the late 1980s and the 1990s, when the newly admitted Brisbane Bears had colours and jumper designs clashing with that of Hawthorn, which necessitated the need for clubs to come up with away colours.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] All AFL teams now have designated clash guernseys, which are worn in matches when the home guernseys of the teams playing are deemed to be too similar to distinguish.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Often white shorts only are used to distinguish between home and away teams, this has been criticised for not providing sufficient distinction between teams that play in similar colours or guernsey designs.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] This combination happened again in 2019, creating again more controversy with the clash being created largely because Geelong wore blue shorts and Collingwood wore white shorts.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Additionally, in the 2021 Anzac Day clash, both Collingwood and Essendon wore predominantly black Anzac Day jumpers, with the only distinction between the teams being Essendon's white shorts, with spectators experiencing difficulty in telling apart the teams.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] This happened again between the two teams on ANZAC Day 2023 with both teams wearing mostly black jumpers with white (Collingwood's white stripes and Essendon jumper numbers) and red (Essendon's red sash and Collingwood's Emirates and KFC sponsorship).
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In some cases, individual clubs may have informal agreements around what guernsey designs to wear in order to avoid clashes.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] This came out after the aforementioned 2019 Geelong-Collingwood match.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In the AFL Grand Final, the team that finishes higher during the regular season has the right to choose the colours they play in, with the lower-ranked team to accommodate this accordingly.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] 's white home (left) and grey away (right) uniforms in 2018.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Baseball teams typically wear white at home and gray at road games.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Originally, Major League Baseball teams were primarily distinguished by the colours of their stockings.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In 1882, the National League assigned different stocking colours to the member clubs; the league also assigned jersey and cap colours, but by player position rather than by club.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Cincinnati Reds were known as the "Red Legs" and "Red Stockings" during the early 1900s.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] By the end of the 19th century, it became common for teams to wear white uniforms at home, and grey in road games.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Some teams used road uniforms of solid dark blue or black.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] An early example of this is the Brooklyn Superbas, who started to use a blue pattern for their road uniforms in 1907.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Both the home and away teams' uniforms also contained trim in the team colours.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In 1916, on the New York Giants' road uniforms, purple lines gave their uniforms a tartan-like effect and another kind of road uniform was a solid dark blue or black material with white around this time.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Kansas City Athletics home and road uniforms were changed by Charles O.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Finley in 1963, to the colours of gold and green.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Some teams used powder blue for their road uniforms from the 1970s to the early 1990s.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Aside from the obvious need to distinguish one team from the other, conventional wisdom held that it was more difficult to properly launder uniforms while on a road trip, thus the "road grays" helped to hide accumulated soil.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] This convention continued well after its original premise was nullified by the issuance of multiple uniforms and the growth of the laundromat industry.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Typically, home uniforms feature the team's nickname, while away uniforms feature the name of the team's geographic designation; there are eight teams that are exceptions to this rules: the Tampa Bay Rays, Los Angeles Angels, Philadelphia Phillies, St.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Louis Cardinals, Washington Nationals, Miami Marlins, Detroit Tigers and New York Yankees.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Cardinals, Phillies, Rays and Angels wear their team nickname on both home and away jerseys, although the Cardinals now wear alternates (cream at home, powder blue on the road) with the city name.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Marlins' home and away jerseys feature the city name, but a black alternate has the team nickname.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Tigers, Nationals and Yankees all wear their cap insignia on the left breast of their home jerseys, but the city name on their away jerseys.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In addition to this, some teams have featured mainly their team's location presented on their uniforms both at home and on the road.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Examples include the Rangers (2009-19) and Marlins, whose alternate orange jersey is the only one of the team's four to feature the nickname instead of the city or state name.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Some teams have alternate home uniforms featuring location such as the Colorado Rockies and St.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The Brewers wore a navy jersey with "Milwaukee" on the front frequently both at home and on the road from 2015-19, while the Los Angeles Dodgers have worn an alternate grey jersey with the nickname instead of the city name for most away games since 2014.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Until the 2017–18 season, the rules of the National Basketball Association (NBA) stated that the home team must always wear their light coloured jerseys and the visitors wear their dark jerseys unless otherwise approved.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Most teams' home uniforms are white, with some exceptions, such as the Los Angeles Lakers, who wear yellow at home (although in 2002, to honour Chick Hearn, Jeanie Buss had a white jersey introduced as the third uniform, worn at home).
[src:road-sports/away-colours] But, according to this rule, road uniforms are required at every game in the NBA.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] "Dark" colours worn in road games vary widely among teams.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The use of specially designed Christmas uniforms in NBA games in 2012 led to several "colour vs. colour" match-ups.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Beginning with the 2017–18 season, the home team is allowed to designate whether it will wear a lighter-coloured or darker-coloured jersey.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The visiting team must wear a jersey of sufficient contrast, whether it be white, yellow, or another darker colour.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Furthermore, the NBA eliminated "home" and "away" uniform designations, and began to officially refer to the lighter-coloured jerseys as "Association" uniforms and the darker-coloured jerseys as "Icon" uniforms.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In NCAA Division I college basketball, the home team almost universally wears white uniforms, while the visiting team wears dark colours.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Away kits are a recent development in cricket, as is coloured clothing in general; cricket has been played in all-white clothing for most of its history.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The first professional match played in coloured clothing was in World Series Cricket in Australia in 1979.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The first Cricket World Cup to use coloured kits was the 1992 tournament.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The England team uses one kit for all home and away ODI and Twenty20 matches.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] India also uses a light blue kit for both.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Australia, however, has a separate green ODI home kit, yellow ODI away kit, and black T20 kit.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The home kit is the same colour as the famous "baggy green" cap traditionally worn by Australian Test cricketers, but the yellow away kit is often worn by the Australian team in home matches.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] black (left) and white (right) uniforms in 2018.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In the NHL each team is currently required to have two uniform designs: one with a white base (or sometimes historically, a light colour), and one with a darker-coloured base.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] From the 1970–71 season to the 2002–03 season, NHL teams wore white or yellow colours at home and the darker colours on the road.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] When the Third Jersey Program was introduced in the 1995–96 season, some teams wore third jerseys at home, thus requiring the road team to wear white.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] This problem was rectified at the start of the 2003–04 season, as NHL teams started to wear the dark colour at home and the white for road games; there are occasional single-game exceptions.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The only elements allowed by NHL rules to be interchangeable between the two uniforms is the pants and gloves.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In the minor leagues, teams historically wore light colours (white or yellow) at home and dark colours on the road.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Original hockey jerseys were actually heavily knit sweaters.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] They were light colours for home games and dark colours for road games.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The reason dark-coloured sweaters were part of the "road" uniform was to hide the dirt the sweaters accumulated.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The sweaters were not washed during road trips.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The light or white sweaters were "home" uniforms as the visiting teams necessarily wore the dark.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] This tradition fits the needs of "home/away" distinctions necessary for black-and-white television.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Away colours are used by Jamaica and Australia, two top international teams who both have yellow home kits.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Jamaica's change kit is all-black, Australia's is all-green.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] When the teams meet, one usually changes its kits but there have been games such as a 2011 Test where each team wore predominantly yellow, with Jamaica in black skirts.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Alternative colours are also used where required in the Australasian ANZ Championship.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] It is traditional in rugby (as it was in association football prior to 1921) for the home team to change in the event of a clash.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] This stems partly from teams touring overseas; it was easier for the home side to get an alternative kit.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] At Rugby World Cups, colour clashes are decided by a coin-toss for first choice of kits.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In the 2007 quarter-final between France and New Zealand, the recently redesigned French kit was dark blue and black, and clashed with the All Blacks' kit.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The toss went in favour of France, and New Zealand wore silver shirts in the game in Cardiff.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] However, in the 2011 Rugby World Cup final between those teams, France won the toss and chose to play in its white away kit.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] France's team manager Jo Maso said this decision was because of "the welcome they'd received from the people of New Zealand, the faultless organisation of the tournament and the honour and pleasure of playing... [at] Eden Park".
[src:road-sports/away-colours] England used an all-black second kit at the 2011 World Cup, which caused controversy in the host nation, as black is the home colour of New Zealand.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] England wore the kit in one tournament match, against Argentina.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Critics in England in 2010 said the team was changing away kits unnecessarily and too often as a "marketing ploy".
[src:road-sports/away-colours] Australia, on the other hand, has rarely worn an away kit except against Romania; a white jersey would have been worn in 2011.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] In international rugby, the need for second kits arises most often in the Six Nations, where Scotland, France and Italy all play in different shades of blue.
[src:road-sports/away-colours] The tournament takes the form of a single round-robin with home advantage alternating each year, and it is scheduled so that each of the three aforementioned sides plays one of the other two at home and the other away in a given season.
